138
00:05:52,720 --> 00:05:55,460
provided certain
conditions are met.

139
00:05:55,460 --> 00:05:58,660
So today, again, it's
really about understanding

140
00:05:58,660 --> 00:06:01,330
the science of happiness,
understanding the mechanisms

141
00:06:01,330 --> 00:06:02,890
underlying what
we call happiness.

142
00:06:02,890 --> 00:06:05,440
And providing you a
framework by which

143
00:06:05,440 --> 00:06:08,530
you can pursue and
achieve happiness not just

144
00:06:08,530 --> 00:06:11,410
as a long-term goal and not
just as a day-to-day goal

145
00:06:11,410 --> 00:06:14,290
of little micro exercises
of gratitude, et cetera,

146
00:06:14,290 --> 00:06:16,930
but rather as a way to
think about happiness

147
00:06:16,930 --> 00:06:19,930
as a state that you have
control over, at least

148
00:06:19,930 --> 00:06:21,700
in terms of your
ability to access

149
00:06:21,700 --> 00:06:23,680
what I would call
the algorithms that

150
00:06:23,680 --> 00:06:27,040
enable us or open the
opportunity to experience

151
00:06:27,040 --> 00:06:27,610
happiness.

152
00:06:27,610 --> 00:06:29,650
Now before we begin
today's episode,

153
00:06:29,650 --> 00:06:33,280
I'd like to talk about a very
specific tool that applies yes

154
00:06:33,280 --> 00:06:35,320
to our pursuit of
happiness but actually

155
00:06:35,320 --> 00:06:37,750
to our pursuit of everything,
including quality sleep

156
00:06:37,750 --> 00:06:40,150
and ongoing
motivation, et cetera.

157
00:06:40,150 --> 00:06:42,550
I've talked many, many
times before on this podcast

158
00:06:42,550 --> 00:06:44,830
and on other podcasts,
and on social media

159
00:06:44,830 --> 00:06:47,800
about the critical
value of getting

160
00:06:47,800 --> 00:06:51,130
regular bright light, ideally
sunlight, in your eyes

161
00:06:51,130 --> 00:06:52,540
within the first hour of waking.

162
00:06:52,540 --> 00:06:55,630
Or if the sun isn't out when
you wake up in the morning,

163
00:06:55,630 --> 00:06:57,490
to turn on a lot of
bright artificial lights

164
00:06:57,490 --> 00:06:58,907
and then get
sunlight in your eyes

165
00:06:58,907 --> 00:07:00,680
for anywhere from
5 to 20 minutes,

166
00:07:00,680 --> 00:07:03,940
depending on how cloudy it is
in the early part of the day.

167
00:07:03,940 --> 00:07:06,640
Absolutely outsized
effects mood and focus

168
00:07:06,640 --> 00:07:09,430
during the day and
quality of sleep at night.

169
00:07:09,430 --> 00:07:12,070
Now there's another
sort of central tenet

170
00:07:12,070 --> 00:07:14,682
of getting great sleep
and improving mood

171
00:07:14,682 --> 00:07:15,890
and focus throughout the day.

172
00:07:15,890 --> 00:07:18,070
And that's to avoid
bright artificial light

173
00:07:18,070 --> 00:07:20,750
exposure to your eyes between
the hours of about 10 PM

174
00:07:20,750 --> 00:07:21,880
to 4:00 AM.

175
00:07:21,880 --> 00:07:24,730
Now leaving shift workers aside,
and we have an entire episode

176
00:07:24,730 --> 00:07:27,160
devoted to shift work, most
people are asleep at night

177
00:07:27,160 --> 00:07:28,450
and awake during the day.

178
00:07:28,450 --> 00:07:31,570
And you would be wise to
avoid exposure of your eyes

179
00:07:31,570 --> 00:07:33,790
to bright artificial light
between the hours of 10:00

180
00:07:33,790 --> 00:07:35,313
PM and 4:00 AM.

181
00:07:35,313 --> 00:07:37,480
If you're going to use
screens or artificial lights,

182
00:07:37,480 --> 00:07:39,890
dim them down as far as you can.

183
00:07:39,890 --> 00:07:42,190
Now there are several studies
that point to the fact

184
00:07:42,190 --> 00:07:44,923
that one of the major
issues with getting

185
00:07:44,923 --> 00:07:47,090
bright light in your eyes
between the hours of 10:00

186
00:07:47,090 --> 00:07:50,020
PM and 4:00 AM is that
it has a negative impact

187
00:07:50,020 --> 00:07:52,900
on the so-called dopaminergic or
dopamine circuits of the brain

188
00:07:52,900 --> 00:07:55,600
and body, which can
enhance depression.

189
00:07:55,600 --> 00:07:59,050
That is lead to ongoing
lower mood and affect.

190
00:07:59,050 --> 00:08:00,550
So that's a reason
to dim the lights

191
00:08:00,550 --> 00:08:03,070
or avoid bright lights
between 10:00 PM and 4:00 AM.

192
00:08:03,070 --> 00:08:06,670
However, I and many others
need to use artificial light

193
00:08:06,670 --> 00:08:09,400
and screens sometimes, even
between the hours of 10:00

194
00:08:09,400 --> 00:08:11,860
PM and midnight or even
midnight to 3:00 AM,

195
00:08:11,860 --> 00:08:15,220
depending on what's going
on in my life or your life.

196
00:08:15,220 --> 00:08:17,125
That may include you as well.

197
00:08:17,125 --> 00:08:19,000
Now it turns out that
there are powerful ways

198
00:08:19,000 --> 00:08:23,020
to offset some, not all, but
some of the negative effects

199
00:08:23,020 --> 00:08:25,460
of viewing artificial lights
between the hours of 10:00

200
00:08:25,460 --> 00:08:26,920
PM and 4:00 AM.

201
00:08:26,920 --> 00:08:29,320
And one of the most
powerful ways to do that

202
00:08:29,320 --> 00:08:31,810
is to simply adjust
the overall brightness

203
00:08:31,810 --> 00:08:34,000
of your artificial
lighting throughout the day

204
00:08:34,000 --> 00:08:35,320
and in the evening.

205
00:08:35,320 --> 00:08:38,320
So one of the issues nowadays
that we're really facing

206
00:08:38,320 --> 00:08:40,990
is that people are simply not
getting enough bright light

207
00:08:40,990 --> 00:08:43,355
in their eyes from sunlight
or from other sources

208
00:08:43,355 --> 00:08:44,980
during the daytime,
and they're getting

209
00:08:44,980 --> 00:08:47,880
far too much bright
light in their eyes

210
00:08:47,880 --> 00:08:50,820
largely from artificial sources,
of course, in the evening

211
00:08:50,820 --> 00:08:51,540
and at night.

212
00:08:51,540 --> 00:08:53,520
Not just from 10 PM
to 4:00 AM, but also

213
00:08:53,520 --> 00:08:56,620
in the evening hours from 6 to
10 PM and so on and so forth.

214
00:08:56,620 --> 00:08:59,130
So a very simple yet
powerful solution

215
00:08:59,130 --> 00:09:02,340
that supported by peer-reviewed
research in humans

216
00:09:02,340 --> 00:09:05,550
is to try and make your
indoor working and/or home

217
00:09:05,550 --> 00:09:08,232
environment during the
day as bright as possible.

218
00:09:08,232 --> 00:09:10,440
Now, if you can achieve that
through direct sunlight,

219
00:09:10,440 --> 00:09:10,990
terrific.

220
00:09:10,990 --> 00:09:13,800
If you can get outside a lot
during the daytime, terrific.

221
00:09:13,800 --> 00:09:15,300
But many people simply cannot.

222
00:09:15,300 --> 00:09:18,580
But most people do have some
windows in their environment.

223
00:09:18,580 --> 00:09:20,370
I realize some don't
but, most people do.

224
00:09:20,370 --> 00:09:22,050
And as a consequence,
most people

225
00:09:22,050 --> 00:09:27,600
are using rather dim artificial
lighting indoors during the day

226
00:09:27,600 --> 00:09:29,700
and then very bright
artificial lighting

227
00:09:29,700 --> 00:09:33,262
indoors in the evening, and
at night, that's a problem.

228
00:09:33,262 --> 00:09:34,970
And if you think about
it, logically, you

229
00:09:34,970 --> 00:09:36,920
want to do the exact reverse.

230
00:09:36,920 --> 00:09:39,020
So it's been shown
that if you simply

231
00:09:39,020 --> 00:09:41,270
increase the amount of
bright artificial light

232
00:09:41,270 --> 00:09:43,940
that you were exposed to
during the day, and remember

233
00:09:43,940 --> 00:09:47,390
this is not an excuse to not get
your morning sunlight viewing,

234
00:09:47,390 --> 00:09:50,668
but in addition to that, to make
your indoor artificial lights

235
00:09:50,668 --> 00:09:52,460
very bright, bright,
bright, bright, bright

236
00:09:52,460 --> 00:09:53,540
throughout the day.

237
00:09:53,540 --> 00:09:58,250
And then much dimmer from the
hours of 6:00 PM until bedtime.

238
00:09:58,250 --> 00:10:00,170
Or if you can't do
that, then maybe as soon

239
00:10:00,170 --> 00:10:03,710
as you get home from about
8:00 PM until bedtime.

240
00:10:03,710 --> 00:10:05,630
And then dim them way,
way down between 10:00

241
00:10:05,630 --> 00:10:07,790
PM and 4:00 AM or off entirely.

242
00:10:07,790 --> 00:10:10,130
That's going to be
a far better pattern

243
00:10:10,130 --> 00:10:12,470
for your sleep-wake
cycles, focus, mood, et

244
00:10:12,470 --> 00:10:14,730
cetera than what
most people do, which

245
00:10:14,730 --> 00:10:16,730
is to have a few windows
in their indoor working

246
00:10:16,730 --> 00:10:20,060
environment during the day and
keep the indoor lights rather

247
