00:19:58,350 --> 00:20:00,150
of what happiness is.

492
00:20:00,150 --> 00:20:02,660
So that's really important to
understand and to keep in mind

493
00:20:02,660 --> 00:20:03,660
throughout this episode.

494
00:20:03,660 --> 00:20:08,910
It doesn't mean that we cannot
have a strong data-driven

495
00:20:08,910 --> 00:20:11,398
conversation about happiness
and what brings us to a state

496
00:20:11,398 --> 00:20:11,940
of happiness.

497
00:20:11,940 --> 00:20:15,360
But it's very important to
understand that language is not

498
00:20:15,360 --> 00:20:18,780
an ideal and maybe even
a deficient tool in terms

499
00:20:18,780 --> 00:20:22,380
of describing our emotions and
our states of mind and body.

500
00:20:22,380 --> 00:20:24,990
Now equally important
is to understand

501
00:20:24,990 --> 00:20:27,930
that while we do have
neurotransmitters,

502
00:20:27,930 --> 00:20:30,660
that is, the chemicals
that are released between

503
00:20:30,660 --> 00:20:32,730
neurons, nerve cells
that allow neurons

504
00:20:32,730 --> 00:20:36,360
to communicate, things
like glutamate and gaba,

505
00:20:36,360 --> 00:20:37,380
for instance.

506
00:20:37,380 --> 00:20:39,780
And we have what are
called modulators.

507
00:20:39,780 --> 00:20:41,400
These are chemicals
also released

508
00:20:41,400 --> 00:20:46,020
by neurons that impact the
electrical firing and chemical

509
00:20:46,020 --> 00:20:47,100
release of other neurons.

510
00:20:47,100 --> 00:20:51,510
Things like serotonin, and
dopamine, and acetylcholine,

511
00:20:51,510 --> 00:20:52,950
and epinephrine.

512
00:20:52,950 --> 00:20:55,800
Neuromodulators and
neurotransmitters

513
00:20:55,800 --> 00:21:00,120
are always present in a
cocktail in our brain and body.

514
00:21:00,120 --> 00:21:02,430
That is, they are present
in different ratios

515
00:21:02,430 --> 00:21:03,670
and at different levels.

516
00:21:03,670 --> 00:21:06,000
So we need to completely
discard with the idea

517
00:21:06,000 --> 00:21:10,290
that any one neurotransmitter
or any one neuromodulator

518
00:21:10,290 --> 00:21:13,920
is solely responsible
for a state of happiness

519
00:21:13,920 --> 00:21:17,620
or for a lack of state of
happiness, for that matter.

520
00:21:17,620 --> 00:21:21,340
That said, it is true
that for people that

521
00:21:21,340 --> 00:21:24,640
tend to have lower baseline
levels of, for instance,

522
00:21:24,640 --> 00:21:27,880
dopamine, their
levels of happiness,

523
00:21:27,880 --> 00:21:29,740
or we should say their
self-reported levels

524
00:21:29,740 --> 00:21:32,890
of happiness, tend to
be lower than for those

525
00:21:32,890 --> 00:21:36,340
that have greatly elevated
baseline levels of dopamine.

526
00:21:36,340 --> 00:21:38,350
Now, this can be
best appreciated

527
00:21:38,350 --> 00:21:41,440
at the extremes
where, for instance,

528
00:21:41,440 --> 00:21:43,690
in conditions like
Parkinson's disease

529
00:21:43,690 --> 00:21:46,330
or other conditions where
people's levels of dopamine

530
00:21:46,330 --> 00:21:49,460
in their brain is
severely depleted.

531
00:21:49,460 --> 00:21:52,760
Mind you, we also see this
in drug-addicted individuals

532
00:21:52,760 --> 00:21:55,310
that are in a withdrawal state
because they're trying to quit

533
00:21:55,310 --> 00:21:57,680
or they don't have access to the
drug that normally stimulates

534
00:21:57,680 --> 00:21:58,513
release of dopamine.

535
00:21:58,513 --> 00:22:01,280
Think the cocaine addict
who can't get cocaine.

536
00:22:01,280 --> 00:22:02,720
Or the methamphetamine
addict that

537
00:22:02,720 --> 00:22:06,670
can't or is trying to avoid
taking methamphetamine.

538
00:22:06,670 --> 00:22:09,640
Or the Parkinson's patient
who has fewer dopamine

539
00:22:09,640 --> 00:22:11,620
neurons because
they degenerated.

540
00:22:11,620 --> 00:22:14,440
Those individuals do tend
to be more depressed.

541
00:22:14,440 --> 00:22:15,880
They tend to have lower affect.

542
00:22:15,880 --> 00:22:17,500
They are less happy.

543
00:22:17,500 --> 00:22:20,860
At least, that's how they report
themselves to be emotionally.

544
00:22:20,860 --> 00:22:23,590
And that's what we observe when
we look at them behaviorally

545
00:22:23,590 --> 00:22:26,710
in terms of the amount of
smiling, the amount of energy

546
00:22:26,710 --> 00:22:28,240
they seem to have.

547
00:22:28,240 --> 00:22:30,010
At the opposite extreme.

548
00:22:30,010 --> 00:22:33,160
And while still focusing
on the kind of pathology

549
00:22:33,160 --> 00:22:35,530
of neurotransmitter and
neuromodulator systems,

550
00:22:35,530 --> 00:22:39,910
an individual who is in
a manic phase of bipolar

551
00:22:39,910 --> 00:22:43,300
will tend to have very
elevated levels of dopamine.

552
00:22:43,300 --> 00:22:45,100
And those people will
talk a mile a minute,

553
00:22:45,100 --> 00:22:46,360
and they won't require sleep.

554
00:22:46,360 --> 00:22:49,458
And at least to them, every
idea is an exciting idea and one

555
00:22:49,458 --> 00:22:50,500
that they want to pursue.

556
00:22:50,500 --> 00:22:54,790
We did an entire episode about
bipolar depression, A.K.A.

557
00:22:54,790 --> 00:22:55,498
Bipolar disorder.

558
00:22:55,498 --> 00:22:57,540
So if you'd like to learn
more about that, please

559
00:22:57,540 --> 00:22:58,690
check out that episode.

560
00:22:58,690 --> 00:23:00,680
That and all other
episodes of the podcast,

561
00:23:00,680 --> 00:23:03,790
of course, you can find it
hubermanlab.com in all formats.

562
00:23:03,790 --> 00:23:06,520
But the point here is
that very low levels

563
00:23:06,520 --> 00:23:09,640
are very high levels of
dopamine are correlated

564
00:23:09,640 --> 00:23:13,720
with certain states of,
for instance, low happiness

565
00:23:13,720 --> 00:23:15,722
or the absence of happiness.

566
00:23:15,722 --> 00:23:17,680
We could even call it
depression in some cases.

567
00:23:17,680 --> 00:23:20,500
Or extreme happiness
or even euphoria.

568
00:23:20,500 --> 00:23:22,150
Sometimes even
inappropriate euphoria,

569
00:23:22,150 --> 00:23:25,300
as is the case with
bipolar depression

570
00:23:25,300 --> 00:23:30,570
or sometimes called bipolar
mania or bipolar disorder.

571
00:23:30,570 --> 00:23:34,610
Now, of course, there's a range
in between depressed and manic.

572
00:23:34,610 --> 00:23:38,670
And most people, fortunately
reside somewhere in that range.

573
00:23:38,670 --> 00:23:40,350
And it is indeed a continuum.

574
00:23:40,350 --> 00:23:43,070
And I think it's safe to
say that levels of dopamine

575
00:23:43,070 --> 00:23:45,260
probably do correlate
with levels of happiness.

576
00:23:45,260 --> 00:23:48,320
But there is no
one single chemical

577
00:23:48,320 --> 00:23:54,920
nor chemical signature, that is,
no specific recipe of two parts

578
00:23:54,920 --> 00:23:57,290
dopamine, to one part
serotonin, to one part

579
00:23:57,290 --> 00:24:01,580
acetylcholine that we can
say equates to happiness.

580
00:24:01,580 --> 00:24:03,410
Indeed there's now
tremendous controversy

581
00:24:03,410 --> 00:24:05,540
as to whether or not,
for instance, having

582
00:24:05,540 --> 00:24:08,060
lower levels of
serotonin is actually

583
00:24:08,060 --> 00:24:10,242
the cause of depression
or merely correlates

584
00:24:10,242 --> 00:24:12,200
with depression or maybe
doesn't even correlate

585
00:24:12,200 --> 00:24:13,200
with depression, at all.

586
00:24:13,200 --> 00:24:14,780
This became especially
controversial

587
00:24:14,780 --> 00:24:17,450
because, in the last year,
the so-called serotonin

588
00:24:17,450 --> 00:24:20,510
hypothesis of depression has
been called into question.

589
00:24:20,510 --> 00:24:24,260
And indeed, it does seem to be
the case that for individuals

590
00:24:24,260 --> 00:24:26,810
that are depressed,
their levels of serotonin

591
00:24:26,810 --> 00:24:28,650
can sometimes be normal.

592
00:24:28,650 --> 00:24:31,440
However, and this is
an important however,

593
00:24:31,440 --> 00:24:33,620
that does not mean that
administering drugs

594
00:24:33,620 --> 00:24:36,110
that increase levels of
serotonin in depressed people

595
00:24:36,110 --> 00:24:39,050
does not sometimes
and indeed often help

596
00:24:39,050 --> 00:24:40,515
ameliorate some
of their symptoms.

597
00:24:40,515 --> 00:24:42,890
And I should mention that many
of the selective serotonin

598
00:24:42,890 --> 00:24:43,890
reuptake inhibitors.

599
00:24:43,890 --> 00:24:46,940
So-called SSRIs such
as Prozac and Zoloft,

600
00:24:46,940 --> 00:24:49,910
et cetera, are still
considered excellent treatments

601
00:24:49,910 --> 00:24:52,950
for conditions like OCD
and so on and so forth.

602
00:24:52,950 --> 00:24:55,410
But what I'm trying to do is
make two important points.

603
00:24:55,410 --> 00:25:00,650
First of all, that language
is not a great indicator

604
00:25:00,650 --> 00:25:01,890
of internal state.

605
00:25:01,890 --> 00:25:04,465
Especially when trying to
understand other people's

606
00:25:04,465 --> 00:25:05,090
internal state.

607
00:25:05,090 --> 00:25:08,210
And that is especially true
for things like happiness.

608
00:25:08,210 --> 00:25:10,670
And that there is
no one chemical

609
00:25:10,670 --> 00:25:13,610
signature of happiness.

610
00:25:13,610 --> 00:25:15,910
There's no one neural
modulator or combinations

611
00:25:15,910 --> 00:25:17,560
of neuromodulators
that we can say

612
00:25:17,560 --> 00:25:19,690
is the cocktail for happiness.

613
00:25:19,690 --> 00:25:24,140
But, and it's a very
important, but when

614
00:25:24,140 --> 00:25:26,570
levels of dopamine
and serotonin tend

615
00:25:26,570 --> 00:25:29,420
to be chronically
low for an individual

616
00:25:29,420 --> 00:25:31,790
below their typical
baseline, they

617
00:25:31,790 --> 00:25:34,520
will, yes, tend to
be lower in affect

618
00:25:34,520 --> 00:25:37,800
and have lower mood and less
episodes of happiness per day,

619
00:25:37,800 --> 00:25:40,380
per week, per month,
per year, et cetera.

620
00:25:40,380 --> 00:25:43,470
Conversely, when an
individual has elevations

621
00:25:43,470 --> 00:25:44,910
in dopamine and
serotonin levels,

622
00:25:44,910 --> 00:25:47,550
in particular dopamine levels
and the other so-called

623
00:25:47,550 --> 00:25:50,770
catecholamines, which include
epinephrine and norepinephrine.

624
00:25:50,770 --> 00:25:53,940
So the catecholamines are
dopamine, epinephrine,

625
00:25:53,940 --> 00:25:54,870
and norepinephrine.

626
00:25:54,870 --> 00:25:56,580
They're all very
similar biochemically.

627
00:25:56,580 --> 00:26:00,600
They all lead to states of
elevated motivation, energy,

628
00:26:00,600 --> 00:26:01,920
and so on.

629
00:26:01,920 --> 00:26:04,830
When those chemicals are
elevated above baseline,

630
00:26:04,830 --> 00:26:08,400
people do tend to have elevated
sense of mood and well-being,

631
00:26:08,400 --> 00:26:10,860
and in particular
sense of possibility

632
00:26:10,860 --> 00:26:12,780
about what they
can do in the world

633
00:26:12,780 --> 00:26:14,950
and what the world
can offer them.

634
00:26:14,950 --> 00:26:17,790
So we need to acknowledge
those two features of language

635
00:26:17,790 --> 00:26:21,120
and neurochemistry as we
wade into the discussion

636
00:26:21,120 --> 00:26:23,580
about the psychology
of happiness.

637
00:26:23,580 --> 00:26:26,910
And, in particular, about
the controlled experiments

638
00:26:26,910 --> 00:26:29,550
that have been done in
excellent laboratories focused

639
00:26:29,550 --> 00:26:32,460
on the psychology of happiness
and what brings happiness

640
00:26:32,460 --> 00:26:33,510
and what does not.

641
00:26:33,510 --> 00:26:36,010
There have been some excellent
studies on happiness.

642
00:26:36,010 --> 00:26:38,850
And these come in
two forms generally.

643
00:26:38,850 --> 00:26:42,150
One form of these
studies is individuals

644
00:26:42,150 --> 00:26:43,320
come into a laboratory.

645
00:26:43,320 --> 00:26:45,630
They participate in an
experiment over the course

646
00:26:45,630 --> 00:26:47,130
of a day or months.

647
00:26:47,130 --> 00:26:49,540
And then, data are
collected analyzed,

648
00:26:49,540 --> 00:26:53,430
and the papers are submitted,
and published, and discussed.

649
00:26:53,430 --> 00:26:56,040
The other form is so-called
longitudinal study.

650
00:26:56,040 --> 00:26:58,050
Where individuals come
into the laboratory,

651
00:26:58,050 --> 00:27:00,930
and they are studied over
a very long period of time.

652
00:27:00,930 --> 00:27:06,980
Ranging from months to years
and sometimes even decades.

653
00:27:06,980 --> 00:27:12,260
And then, the variables of
age, life circumstances,

654
00:27:12,260 --> 00:27:15,590
and other factors can be
incorporated into the data.

655
00:27:15,590 --> 00:27:19,070
And typically, there
are multiple papers,

656
00:27:19,070 --> 00:27:22,340
there's data published
throughout the longitudinal

657
00:27:22,340 --> 00:27:24,050
study, or sometimes
it's just one paper

658
00:27:24,050 --> 00:27:26,510
at the end of the
longitudinal study.

659
00:27:26,510 --> 00:27:29,330
Let's talk about one of
the more famous and perhaps

660
00:27:29,330 --> 00:27:33,200
the longest-running
longitudinal study on happiness.

661
00:27:33,200 --> 00:27:36,410
This is a study that was
initiated or conceived

662
00:27:36,410 --> 00:27:38,870
in 1938 at Harvard University.

663
00:27:38,870 --> 00:27:40,910
The so-called Harvard
Happiness Project.

664
00:27:40,910 --> 00:27:42,660
Some of you probably
heard about this.

665
00:27:42,660 --> 00:27:45,860
It involved Harvard
College sophomores

666
00:27:45,860 --> 00:27:49,400
and other individuals who were
incorporated into this study

667
00:27:49,400 --> 00:27:50,720
as well.

668
00:27:50,720 --> 00:27:54,230
It's a study that initially
had more than a couple

669
00:27:54,230 --> 00:27:55,820
of hundred subjects.

670
00:27:55,820 --> 00:27:58,880
But because some have
either dropped out and not

671
00:27:58,880 --> 00:28:02,660
been able to be contacted and
monitored over time or died,

672
00:28:02,660 --> 00:28:05,390
or for whatever reason,
are no longer participating

673
00:28:05,390 --> 00:28:08,220
in the study, they're very
few of these individuals left.

674
00:28:08,220 --> 00:28:10,557
And yet there's tremendous
power to a study like this.

675
00:28:10,557 --> 00:28:12,890
It's such an impressive study,
and we're all so grateful

676
00:28:12,890 --> 00:28:14,960
that laboratories
at Harvard decided

677
00:28:14,960 --> 00:28:18,560
to initiate and continue
this study because it

678
00:28:18,560 --> 00:28:21,290
is one of the few studies,
perhaps the study that

679
00:28:21,290 --> 00:28:25,010
has allowed us to understand
happiness in our species

680
00:28:25,010 --> 00:28:27,410
over a very long period of time.

681
00:28:27,410 --> 00:28:28,910
Like any study,
it's not perfect.

682
00:28:28,910 --> 00:28:32,600
It didn't include a
lot of matching by sex

683
00:28:32,600 --> 00:28:34,370
or matching by
vocation, or matching

684
00:28:34,370 --> 00:28:35,780
by income and background.

685
00:28:35,780 --> 00:28:38,420
And back then, there was
also a lot less discussion

686
00:28:38,420 --> 00:28:40,560
about trauma and
histories around trauma,

687
00:28:40,560 --> 00:28:42,890
as well as positive
episodes in people's lives.

688
00:28:42,890 --> 00:28:46,580
Nonetheless, there's a lot of
power in a study like this.

689
00:28:46,580 --> 00:28:48,863
And there are some
very basic takeaways,

690
00:28:48,863 --> 00:28:51,530
some of which you may have heard
before but some of which may be

691
00:28:51,530 --> 00:28:54,780
surprising those
of you who haven't.

692
00:28:54,780 --> 00:28:57,680
So one of the key
things about the study

693
00:28:57,680 --> 00:29:00,830
is people in the
study, at least those

694
00:29:00,830 --> 00:29:03,950
who still have intact memory,
which many of them do,

695
00:29:03,950 --> 00:29:06,680
are able to think
back on not just

696
00:29:06,680 --> 00:29:10,370
their previous year or week but
10 years ago, 20 years ago, 50

697
00:29:10,370 --> 00:29:13,700
years ago and compare
what makes them happy

698
00:29:13,700 --> 00:29:15,860
at one age versus another age.

699
00:29:15,860 --> 00:29:18,480
A number of things have
emerged from that conversation.

700
00:29:18,480 --> 00:29:20,798
So I just want to discuss
some of the highlight points

701
00:29:20,798 --> 00:29:22,340
then we'll get into
a little bit more

702
00:29:22,340 --> 00:29:23,910
of the nitty-gritty of the data.

703
00:29:23,910 --> 00:29:27,050
First of all, it's been
discussed many, many times

704
00:29:27,050 --> 00:29:31,670
that the total amount of
income that an individual makes

705
00:29:31,670 --> 00:29:34,550
or has, and again, this
could be income from work,

706
00:29:34,550 --> 00:29:37,280
or it could be money
that they inherited,

707
00:29:37,280 --> 00:29:42,330
does not seem to directly relate
to their level of happiness.

708
00:29:42,330 --> 00:29:45,980
Now a lot of people take
that point and think,

709
00:29:45,980 --> 00:29:47,720
oh, money doesn't matter.

710
00:29:47,720 --> 00:29:51,500
Other people hear that point
and think to themselves,

711
00:29:51,500 --> 00:29:54,528
yeah, right, easy to say
if you have a lot of money.

712
00:29:54,528 --> 00:29:56,570
We'll talk about the
interpretation of those data

713
00:29:56,570 --> 00:29:58,080
in just a few minutes.

714
00:29:58,080 --> 00:30:00,830
But I do want to
earmark that finding.

715
00:30:00,830 --> 00:30:07,760
Because I agree that while
money or total resources itself

716
00:30:07,760 --> 00:30:11,690
does not predict happiness
in any kind of direct way,

717
00:30:11,690 --> 00:30:13,400
that is not the
same thing as saying

718
00:30:13,400 --> 00:30:16,550
having very few resources will
make you happier, of course.

719
00:30:16,550 --> 00:30:18,530
I don't think anyone
would imagine that.

720
00:30:18,530 --> 00:30:22,340
But it also tends to overlook
an important point, which

721
00:30:22,340 --> 00:30:24,710
is something that I certainly
have learned to appreciate

722
00:30:24,710 --> 00:30:27,650
in my life and something
that I especially appreciated

723
00:30:27,650 --> 00:30:30,482
when I was a student
and post-doc, which

724
00:30:30,482 --> 00:30:31,190
is the following.

725
00:30:31,190 --> 00:30:33,530
People will say money
can't buy happiness.

726
00:30:33,530 --> 00:30:36,870
And we'll talk about the buy
aspect of that in a moment.

727
00:30:36,870 --> 00:30:38,150
And indeed, that's true.

728
00:30:38,150 --> 00:30:40,682
If you look at this
longitudinal study or you

729
00:30:40,682 --> 00:30:42,140
look at other
studies that are done

730
00:30:42,140 --> 00:30:44,270
on a more short-term basis.

731
00:30:44,270 --> 00:30:46,820
Once people get past a
certain level of income

732
00:30:46,820 --> 00:30:51,000
relative to their cost of
living, the amount of happiness

733
00:30:51,000 --> 00:30:52,620
does not scale with that income.

734
00:30:52,620 --> 00:30:55,800
That is, for every
additional $1,000 or $10,000

735
00:30:55,800 --> 00:30:57,330
that they earn,
they don't report

736
00:30:57,330 --> 00:31:00,270
being that much happier
on a daily basis.

737
00:31:00,270 --> 00:31:06,660
Now that said, I venture the
