00:51:53,968 --> 00:51:55,510
And, of course, most
of us don't know

1220
00:51:55,510 --> 00:51:57,550
how long we will
live anyway, but we

1221
00:51:57,550 --> 00:51:58,960
do have some general sense.

1222
00:51:58,960 --> 00:52:02,290
I mean, very few people
live past the age of 100.

1223
00:52:02,290 --> 00:52:05,020
Many people live to be 70 or 80.

1224
00:52:05,020 --> 00:52:08,950
And again, life span
is extending as far

1225
00:52:08,950 --> 00:52:11,080
as we know from year to year.

1226
00:52:11,080 --> 00:52:14,440
But, in general, people report
that on their birthdays.

1227
00:52:14,440 --> 00:52:16,210
And I should say these
are for birthdays

1228
00:52:16,210 --> 00:52:20,050
aged 25 or later, at
least in the studies

1229
00:52:20,050 --> 00:52:21,798
I was able to access.

1230
00:52:21,798 --> 00:52:23,590
I don't think that a
lot of three-year-olds

1231
00:52:23,590 --> 00:52:25,923
sit around comparing themselves
to other three-year-olds

1232
00:52:25,923 --> 00:52:27,820
and how well they're
doing or 12-year-olds.

1233
00:52:27,820 --> 00:52:30,550
You can imagine some people
might do that at 18, et cetera.

1234
00:52:30,550 --> 00:52:32,890
But it's really by the
mid-20s that people

1235
00:52:32,890 --> 00:52:35,050
start evaluating
themselves to their peers

1236
00:52:35,050 --> 00:52:38,050
in terms of life progression
and so-called milestones.

1237
00:52:38,050 --> 00:52:40,660
It's been argued that that's
one of the reasons why people

1238
00:52:40,660 --> 00:52:42,790
report lower affect,
lower levels of happiness

1239
00:52:42,790 --> 00:52:43,540
on their birthday.

1240
00:52:43,540 --> 00:52:45,498
Something that's a little
bit counterintuitive.

1241
00:52:45,498 --> 00:52:47,207
And, of course, there
are things that are

1242
00:52:47,207 --> 00:52:48,730
anti-correlated with happiness.

1243
00:52:48,730 --> 00:52:51,040
I'd be remiss if I didn't
mention a few of these.

1244
00:52:51,040 --> 00:52:54,850
That's longitudinal study,
the Harvard happiness project

1245
00:52:54,850 --> 00:52:57,820
has reported, for
instance, that people that

1246
00:52:57,820 --> 00:53:00,940
are chronic smokers of
nicotine and chronic

1247
00:53:00,940 --> 00:53:03,850
consumers of alcohol, in
particular alcoholics.

1248
00:53:03,850 --> 00:53:05,620
That is, people who
suffer from alcoholism

1249
00:53:05,620 --> 00:53:08,950
or what sometimes is called
alcohol use disorder that

1250
00:53:08,950 --> 00:53:11,260
is strongly anti-correlated
with happiness.

1251
00:53:11,260 --> 00:53:13,390
And I should also mention
that the family members,

1252
00:53:13,390 --> 00:53:15,130
and in particular,
the romantic partners

1253
00:53:15,130 --> 00:53:19,720
of people who are chronic
smokers and the partners

1254
00:53:19,720 --> 00:53:23,200
of people who are chronic
alcohol users, often

1255
00:53:23,200 --> 00:53:24,790
will report lower
levels of happiness.

1256
00:53:24,790 --> 00:53:26,830
Especially if they
themselves are not

1257
00:53:26,830 --> 00:53:31,300
chronic smokers or regular
consumers of alcohol.

1258
00:53:31,300 --> 00:53:35,020
So we've done episodes on
nicotine in particular,

1259
00:53:35,020 --> 00:53:36,730
and that touched on
smoking, of course.

1260
00:53:36,730 --> 00:53:39,370
And we've done an
episode on alcohol

1261
00:53:39,370 --> 00:53:41,740
and the effects of
alcohol on health.

1262
00:53:41,740 --> 00:53:43,810
Again, you can find
those at hubermanlab.com.

1263
00:53:43,810 --> 00:53:46,990
This study from the
Harvard happiness project

1264
00:53:46,990 --> 00:53:49,690
really has strong
data supporting

1265
00:53:49,690 --> 00:53:52,810
the fact that avoiding
being a nicotine smoker.

1266
00:53:52,810 --> 00:53:54,888
There are positive health
effects of nicotine

1267
00:53:54,888 --> 00:53:56,680
that are discussed in
the episode nicotine.

1268
00:53:56,680 --> 00:53:59,440
But being a-- but smoking
nicotine, in particular,

1269
00:53:59,440 --> 00:54:03,460
is counterproductive for
people's at least self-reported

1270
00:54:03,460 --> 00:54:05,530
happiness and certainly
overall health.

1271
00:54:05,530 --> 00:54:08,140
I think there's zero question
that smoking increases

1272
00:54:08,140 --> 00:54:09,730
cancers of different kinds.

1273
00:54:09,730 --> 00:54:11,650
And that alcohol consumption.

1274
00:54:11,650 --> 00:54:14,440
And in particular, alcohol
consumption beyond two

1275
00:54:14,440 --> 00:54:16,390
drinks per week.

1276
00:54:16,390 --> 00:54:18,850
Two drinks being the
typical volume of a beer,

1277
00:54:18,850 --> 00:54:20,920
a glass of wine or
cocktail, et cetera,

1278
00:54:20,920 --> 00:54:23,087
is detrimental for
various aspects of health.

1279
00:54:23,087 --> 00:54:24,670
And, of course, there
are other things

1280
00:54:24,670 --> 00:54:28,150
that you could imagine would
relate to a lack of happiness.

1281
00:54:28,150 --> 00:54:30,230
For instance, a major trauma.

1282
00:54:30,230 --> 00:54:32,500
Physical or emotional trauma.

1283
00:54:32,500 --> 00:54:34,690
That could include the loss
of a major relationship,

1284
00:54:34,690 --> 00:54:37,000
a death of a close one.

1285
00:54:37,000 --> 00:54:40,210
Being the victim of a violent
crime and things of that sort.

1286
00:54:40,210 --> 00:54:45,070
And yet it's been argued, in
fact, strongly argued that when

1287
00:54:45,070 --> 00:54:49,420
you look at people's levels
of happiness after a trauma,

1288
00:54:49,420 --> 00:54:54,070
that if you wait
about a year or so,

1289
00:54:54,070 --> 00:54:56,230
sometimes is even as
short as three months

1290
00:54:56,230 --> 00:54:59,380
after a trauma, that
people self-reported levels

1291
00:54:59,380 --> 00:55:02,830
of happiness are not
significantly lower than they

1292
00:55:02,830 --> 00:55:04,360
were prior to the trauma.

1293
00:55:04,360 --> 00:55:08,830
Now I very much want to
highlight, underline, and bold

1294
00:55:08,830 --> 00:55:11,322
and asterisks that
statement as one

1295
00:55:11,322 --> 00:55:13,030
that we really need
to explore carefully.

1296
00:55:13,030 --> 00:55:17,230
Because there are other data
that strongly point to the fact

1297
00:55:17,230 --> 00:55:20,080
that major life
traumas can severely

1298
00:55:20,080 --> 00:55:22,270
disrupt one sense of
happiness and well-being.

1299
00:55:22,270 --> 00:55:24,728
And I think as long as we're
going to have this discussion,

1300
00:55:24,728 --> 00:55:27,790
we should point to a useful
definition of trauma.

1301
00:55:27,790 --> 00:55:29,830
And the definition
that I'll paraphrase

1302
00:55:29,830 --> 00:55:33,940
is one that was supplied by a
former guest on the Huberman

1303
00:55:33,940 --> 00:55:37,330
Lab podcast, Dr. Paul Conti,
who's a psychiatrist who's

1304
00:55:37,330 --> 00:55:38,710
written a book called Trauma.

1305
00:55:38,710 --> 00:55:42,492
I personally think it's the
best book on trauma and tools

1306
00:55:42,492 --> 00:55:43,450
for alleviating trauma.

1307
00:55:43,450 --> 00:55:47,350
It's incredibly thorough, easy
to read, and well-informed.

1308
00:55:47,350 --> 00:55:49,897
And here again,
I'm paraphrasing,

1309
00:55:49,897 --> 00:55:52,480
but Dr. Conti describes trauma
as something that fundamentally

1310
00:55:52,480 --> 00:55:56,440
changes the way that our
brain and body function

1311
00:55:56,440 --> 00:55:58,990
in a way that makes
other aspects of living

1312
00:55:58,990 --> 00:56:00,580
more challenging.

1313
00:56:00,580 --> 00:56:03,520
Again, an event, either
emotional or physical,

1314
00:56:03,520 --> 00:56:05,560
or both, that fundamentally
changes the way

1315
00:56:05,560 --> 00:56:10,000
that our brain and/or
body, our nervous system,

1316
00:56:10,000 --> 00:56:13,420
and other organs function
in a way that prevents us

1317
00:56:13,420 --> 00:56:15,910
from enjoying daily activities.

1318
00:56:15,910 --> 00:56:17,830
And that could even be
ongoing distraction.

1319
00:56:17,830 --> 00:56:20,110
Traumas can create
rumination, or they

1320
00:56:20,110 --> 00:56:22,870
can create obsessive thought,
or they can create dissociation.

1321
00:56:22,870 --> 00:56:24,200
Any number of different things.

1322
00:56:24,200 --> 00:56:26,830
Again check out that
episode with Dr. Paul Conti

1323
00:56:26,830 --> 00:56:28,570
if you'd like to learn
more about trauma

1324
00:56:28,570 --> 00:56:29,470
and how it manifests.

1325
00:56:29,470 --> 00:56:32,020
But the idea that's
been put forth

1326
00:56:32,020 --> 00:56:34,750
by a number of researchers
in the field of happiness

1327
00:56:34,750 --> 00:56:37,450
that three months after
a major trauma, people

1328
00:56:37,450 --> 00:56:40,870
aren't reported that they
are feeling any less happy

1329
00:56:40,870 --> 00:56:43,270
than before the trauma,
that was surprising to me.

1330
00:56:43,270 --> 00:56:46,220
So I went into this
literature a bit more deeply.

1331
00:56:46,220 --> 00:56:49,480
One of the basis of that
general line of thinking

1332
00:56:49,480 --> 00:56:53,290
is a-- what I consider a now
classic and very important

1333
00:56:53,290 --> 00:56:55,270
and frankly excellent
talk that was

1334
00:56:55,270 --> 00:56:58,750
given by Professor Dan Gilbert
on the science of happiness.

1335
00:56:58,750 --> 00:57:01,780
You can find this on YouTube.

1336
00:57:01,780 --> 00:57:04,840
I say a classic one because
it was done some years ago.

1337
00:57:04,840 --> 00:57:06,850
It's received millions of views.

1338
00:57:06,850 --> 00:57:09,100
And one of the points that
he makes in that talk which

1339
00:57:09,100 --> 00:57:11,140
is grounded in
research carried out

1340
00:57:11,140 --> 00:57:14,530
by his laboratory and other
laboratories is that--

1341
00:57:14,530 --> 00:57:16,250
he poses a question.

1342
00:57:16,250 --> 00:57:18,790
He says you know,
let's do a quiz.

1343
00:57:18,790 --> 00:57:21,260
Would you rather be someone
who wins the lottery

1344
00:57:21,260 --> 00:57:23,260
and he shows a picture
of somebody who just won,

1345
00:57:23,260 --> 00:57:25,510
I think it was several
hundreds of millions of dollars

1346
00:57:25,510 --> 00:57:29,140
in the lottery, or was
recently made paraplegic lost

1347
00:57:29,140 --> 00:57:30,950
use of their legs?

1348
00:57:30,950 --> 00:57:34,280
And then goes on to
state that one year

1349
00:57:34,280 --> 00:57:36,210
after people have
won the lottery,

1350
00:57:36,210 --> 00:57:39,860
this major monetary windfall
versus have become paraplegic

1351
00:57:39,860 --> 00:57:42,680
is that their self-reported
levels of happiness

1352
00:57:42,680 --> 00:57:43,770
are the same.

1353
00:57:43,770 --> 00:57:47,030
Which I think is
incredibly surprising.

1354
00:57:47,030 --> 00:57:50,900
I heard this, and I immediately
thought of an experience

1355
00:57:50,900 --> 00:57:54,560
that I've had where I
teach a course at Stanford

1356
00:57:54,560 --> 00:57:57,020
School of Medicine on
neural regeneration.

1357
00:57:57,020 --> 00:57:59,510
And it's actually a course
that I attended some years

1358
00:57:59,510 --> 00:58:01,170
ago when I was a
post-doc at Stanford,

1359
00:58:01,170 --> 00:58:03,000
so well over a decade ago.

1360
00:58:03,000 --> 00:58:05,630
And we had-- excuse me.

1361
00:58:05,630 --> 00:58:09,180
We had an individual
come into the course.

1362
00:58:09,180 --> 00:58:11,030
This was an older gentleman.

1363
00:58:11,030 --> 00:58:13,550
So older meaning he
was in his early 70s.

1364
00:58:13,550 --> 00:58:16,370
And he had become paraplegic
fairly late in life

1365
00:58:16,370 --> 00:58:18,020
from a cycling accident.

1366
00:58:18,020 --> 00:58:23,610
And he was and is
an expert in what

1367
00:58:23,610 --> 00:58:25,410
it is to become a
paraplegic, of course,

1368
00:58:25,410 --> 00:58:27,827
because he had that experience,
but also because he spends

1369
00:58:27,827 --> 00:58:30,120
a lot of his time doing
volunteer work with people who

1370
00:58:30,120 --> 00:58:32,670
have become paraplegic
and have become paraplegic

1371
00:58:32,670 --> 00:58:33,540
at different ages.

1372
00:58:33,540 --> 00:58:37,470
And what he described to me
was that the overall outcomes

1373
00:58:37,470 --> 00:58:39,990
for people that are
rendered paraplegic

1374
00:58:39,990 --> 00:58:43,760
in terms of their mental health
and their physical well-being

1375
00:58:43,760 --> 00:58:46,110
and their management
of general life skills

1376
00:58:46,110 --> 00:58:50,400
scales with how early
they had that injury

1377
00:58:50,400 --> 00:58:52,570
and how long they had
the use of their limbs.

1378
00:58:52,570 --> 00:58:55,300
So it's not straightforward.

1379
00:58:55,300 --> 00:59:00,190
When I heard this result
described by Dr. Dan Gilbert,

1380
00:59:00,190 --> 00:59:02,440
that winning the lottery
and becoming paraplegic

1381
00:59:02,440 --> 00:59:05,230
basically don't impact
your levels of happiness

1382
00:59:05,230 --> 00:59:10,220
to any different degree when
people look back a year later,

1383
00:59:10,220 --> 00:59:13,150
I was pretty surprised
given my experience

1384
00:59:13,150 --> 00:59:15,170
of hearing this
lecture at Stanford.

1385
00:59:15,170 --> 00:59:17,140
So I thought, wow,
from what I understand.

1386
00:59:17,140 --> 00:59:19,360
Indeed, there are people
who are rendered paraplegic

1387
00:59:19,360 --> 00:59:22,000
and manage that
transition very easily.

1388
00:59:22,000 --> 00:59:24,592
It doesn't seem to disrupt
their feelings of well-being,

1389
00:59:24,592 --> 00:59:26,050
et cetera, but for
other people, it

1390
00:59:26,050 --> 00:59:30,610
can be severely disrupting
to their sense of well-being

1391
00:59:30,610 --> 00:59:32,230
and so on and so forth.

1392
00:59:32,230 --> 00:59:35,290
I went back and
examined these data.

1393
00:59:35,290 --> 00:59:37,690
And in fact, a
subsequent talk, it's

1394
00:59:37,690 --> 00:59:40,390
actually a podcast that
was given by Dr. Dan

1395
00:59:40,390 --> 00:59:42,167
Gilbert some years later.

1396
00:59:42,167 --> 00:59:43,750
So this would be
just a few years ago.

1397
00:59:43,750 --> 00:59:46,180
I think in 2019-- there
is a specific date

1398
00:59:46,180 --> 00:59:49,430
in which it was recorded
but just a few years ago.

1399
00:59:49,430 --> 00:59:53,050
And indeed, he corrects
himself in that podcast.

1400
00:59:53,050 --> 00:59:57,040
What he says is that he
misspoke in that earlier talk.

1401
00:59:57,040 --> 01:00:00,550
That the difference in
self-reported levels

1402
01:00:00,550 --> 01:00:03,760
of happiness for those that
have been rendered paraplegic

1403
01:00:03,760 --> 01:00:08,860
for versus those who've won the
lottery is not as great as one

1404
01:00:08,860 --> 01:00:09,445
would expect.

1405
01:00:09,445 --> 01:00:12,070
I think most people would expect
that being rendered paraplegic

1406
01:00:12,070 --> 01:00:14,200
would make people
far less happy.

1407
01:00:14,200 --> 01:00:16,210
That's the expectation,
I think, anyway.

1408
01:00:16,210 --> 01:00:17,890
And that people would
win the lottery,

1409
01:00:17,890 --> 01:00:19,360
at least for some
period of time,

1410
01:00:19,360 --> 01:00:21,190
would be far happier
than they were

1411
01:00:21,190 --> 01:00:23,770
prior to winning the lottery.

1412
01:00:23,770 --> 01:00:26,510
And especially given the
tremendous amount of money.

1413
01:00:26,510 --> 01:00:29,600
And again, the fact that
money can't buy happiness,

1414
01:00:29,600 --> 01:00:32,410
but that money does
indeed enable the ability

1415
01:00:32,410 --> 01:00:34,990
to buffer stress
provided people were

1416
01:00:34,990 --> 01:00:36,490
responsible with
that money and just

1417
01:00:36,490 --> 01:00:38,320
didn't blow it or spend
it all right away.

1418
01:00:38,320 --> 01:00:40,120
That they could start
to afford things

1419
01:00:40,120 --> 01:00:42,730
that they couldn't afford, not
just in terms of luxury items

1420
01:00:42,730 --> 01:00:44,700
but also the
ability to hire help

1421
01:00:44,700 --> 01:00:47,200
that would free up time that
would allow them to do anything

1422
01:00:47,200 --> 01:00:49,997
from travel that they couldn't
access before to meditate

1423
01:00:49,997 --> 01:00:52,580
if that was something that they
didn't have time to do before.

1424
01:00:52,580 --> 01:00:54,020
And so on and so forth.

1425
01:00:54,020 --> 01:00:58,120
So the result quote
unquote that winners

1426
01:00:58,120 --> 01:00:59,710
of the lottery and
recent paraplegics

1427
01:00:59,710 --> 01:01:02,350
have the same levels of
happiness is actually not true.

1428
01:01:02,350 --> 01:01:05,440
At least according to the
author of the original study.

1429
01:01:05,440 --> 01:01:08,950
Now what he did not point to is
the degree to which that is not

1430
01:01:08,950 --> 01:01:11,377
true, but he did point to
the direction of the result.

1431
01:01:11,377 --> 01:01:13,960
And the fact that people who are
rendered paraplegic, in fact,

1432
01:01:13,960 --> 01:01:17,850
are reporting
themselves as less happy

1433
01:01:17,850 --> 01:01:19,560
than they were prior
to their injury.

1434
01:01:19,560 --> 01:01:22,200
And certainly that their
levels of happiness

1435
01:01:22,200 --> 01:01:24,753
are lower than those that
simply won the lottery

1436
01:01:24,753 --> 01:01:26,670
hundreds of millions of
dollars, which I think

1437
01:01:26,670 --> 01:01:28,960
is the more intuitive result.

1438
01:01:28,960 --> 01:01:31,830
And so I think it's important
to be aware of that discrepancy

1439
01:01:31,830 --> 01:01:33,330
because it's something
that was lost

1440
01:01:33,330 --> 01:01:36,270
in the communication
around those results

1441
01:01:36,270 --> 01:01:37,390
the first time around.

1442
01:01:37,390 --> 01:01:40,530
And indeed, Dan Gilbert
is an excellent scientist

1443
01:01:40,530 --> 01:01:44,280
and was quite good about trying
to correct the narrative.

1444
01:01:44,280 --> 01:01:47,178
I myself, as a podcaster
who puts information

1445
01:01:47,178 --> 01:01:49,470
on the internet, know that
the challenges of correcting

1446
01:01:49,470 --> 01:01:52,945
narratives, especially of things
that came out some time ago,

1447
01:01:52,945 --> 01:01:54,570
we always attempt to
do this as best we

1448
01:01:54,570 --> 01:01:57,090
can, but not everyone that
saw that first video will

1449
01:01:57,090 --> 01:02:00,240
necessarily hear the discussion
that has happened subsequently.

1450
01:02:00,240 --> 01:02:05,280
So my hope is that Dr. Gilbert
will interpret me communicating

1451
01:02:05,280 --> 01:02:07,260
this now not as an
attempt to criticize him

1452
01:02:07,260 --> 01:02:09,510
but rather as an attempt
to praise his willingness

1453
01:02:09,510 --> 01:02:12,100
to try and correct the
narrative to be more accurate.

1454
01:02:12,100 --> 01:02:15,090
So to be very clear about what
this study did and didn't show.

1455
01:02:15,090 --> 01:02:18,720
And here, I'm going to
combine these results

1456
01:02:18,720 --> 01:02:21,030
with other studies
that I was able to find

