1517
01:05:05,430 --> 01:05:06,990
Now there is an
important point, or I

1518
01:05:06,990 --> 01:05:10,740
should say the important
point, that we can really

1519
01:05:10,740 --> 01:05:14,640
credit Dan Gilbert and others
in the field of psychology with

1520
01:05:14,640 --> 01:05:16,950
and that we owe them a
great debt of gratitude

1521
01:05:16,950 --> 01:05:21,390
for is that we do
have far more control

1522
01:05:21,390 --> 01:05:24,180
over our levels of happiness
than we might think.

1523
01:05:24,180 --> 01:05:27,420
And many of the
things that reside

1524
01:05:27,420 --> 01:05:29,070
at that level of control.

1525
01:05:29,070 --> 01:05:33,870
That is, the things that we can
do and think and say and access

1526
01:05:33,870 --> 01:05:36,870
don't come from external things.

1527
01:05:36,870 --> 01:05:40,380
They don't come necessarily
from the acquisition of material

1528
01:05:40,380 --> 01:05:42,900
goods, but rather
there are things

1529
01:05:42,900 --> 01:05:47,400
that we can do that can allow
us to so-called synthesize

1530
01:05:47,400 --> 01:05:48,040
happiness.

1531
01:05:48,040 --> 01:05:50,010
And I think this is
one of the great gifts

1532
01:05:50,010 --> 01:05:52,950
of modern psychology is that--

1533
01:05:52,950 --> 01:05:55,620
Dan Gilbert and others, the
Harvard happiness project,

1534
01:05:55,620 --> 01:05:57,690
work at Yale and elsewhere.

1535
01:05:57,690 --> 01:06:01,380
There are excellent labs working
on happiness all over the US

1536
01:06:01,380 --> 01:06:03,580
and all over the world, frankly.

1537
01:06:03,580 --> 01:06:05,550
One of the great gifts
that they've supplied us

1538
01:06:05,550 --> 01:06:07,920
in the form of data
is that there really

1539
01:06:07,920 --> 01:06:11,070
are things that we can all
do and think and access

1540
01:06:11,070 --> 01:06:14,400
to allow ourselves to
so-called synthesize happiness.

1541
01:06:14,400 --> 01:06:17,190
Now, this notion of
synthesizing happiness,

1542
01:06:17,190 --> 01:06:20,070
or synthetic happiness
as it's sometimes called,

1543
01:06:20,070 --> 01:06:22,200
can sometimes ruffle
people's feathers a bit.

1544
01:06:22,200 --> 01:06:25,620
Because people immediately
flip to the idea

1545
01:06:25,620 --> 01:06:27,270
that, oh, you're
just going to tell

1546
01:06:27,270 --> 01:06:30,720
me to be grateful for what
I have or to just navel

1547
01:06:30,720 --> 01:06:32,763
gaze or just to
imagine that I'm happy.

1548
01:06:32,763 --> 01:06:34,680
But that's really not
what synthetic happiness

1549
01:06:34,680 --> 01:06:35,587
is about at all.

1550
01:06:35,587 --> 01:06:37,170
Synthetic happiness
actually has to do

1551
01:06:37,170 --> 01:06:41,250
with some really important
larger principles about the way

1552
01:06:41,250 --> 01:06:43,980
that our emotional
system and the way

1553
01:06:43,980 --> 01:06:48,330
that the reward systems of
our brain really function.

1554
01:06:48,330 --> 01:06:50,550
And they point to
important concepts

1555
01:06:50,550 --> 01:06:52,260
that we're going to now discuss.

1556
01:06:52,260 --> 01:06:55,270
Things like the hedonic
set point, for instance.

1557
01:06:55,270 --> 01:06:57,960
Or the dopamine
system of anticipation

1558
01:06:57,960 --> 01:07:01,350
of rewards versus receiving
words just as a brief insight

1559
01:07:01,350 --> 01:07:02,550
into that.

1560
01:07:02,550 --> 01:07:05,190
Our anticipation of
something positive

1561
01:07:05,190 --> 01:07:08,100
oftentimes leads to
greater increases

1562
01:07:08,100 --> 01:07:09,870
in the sorts of
neurochemicals that

1563
01:07:09,870 --> 01:07:12,390
support a state of
happiness and well-being

1564
01:07:12,390 --> 01:07:15,780
then the actual
acquisition of the thing

1565
01:07:15,780 --> 01:07:17,040
that we're trying to obtain.

