2185
01:33:44,180 --> 01:33:46,340
I think is especially
interesting

2186
01:33:46,340 --> 01:33:49,280
is that regardless
of whether or not

2187
01:33:49,280 --> 01:33:52,460
people were engaging in
activities that they enjoyed

2188
01:33:52,460 --> 01:33:57,770
or not, the tendency for their
mind to wander from an activity

2189
01:33:57,770 --> 01:33:59,990
predicted lower
levels of happiness

2190
01:33:59,990 --> 01:34:02,180
than if they tended to be
focused on the activity

2191
01:34:02,180 --> 01:34:03,710
they were engaged in.

2192
01:34:03,710 --> 01:34:06,480
Now that itself
should be surprising.

2193
01:34:06,480 --> 01:34:09,200
I mean, what that says
is that even if somebody

2194
01:34:09,200 --> 01:34:11,600
was engaged in activity
like cleaning their house

2195
01:34:11,600 --> 01:34:14,600
or doing homework or reading
something that they weren't

2196
01:34:14,600 --> 01:34:18,090
enjoying, if they were focused
on what they were doing,

2197
01:34:18,090 --> 01:34:22,730
they tended to report as happier
than if their mind was drifting

2198
01:34:22,730 --> 01:34:23,610
elsewhere.

2199
01:34:23,610 --> 01:34:26,570
Now this also points to the
idea that perhaps our minds

2200
01:34:26,570 --> 01:34:29,090
drift to unpleasant thoughts
more than pleasant thoughts.

2201
01:34:29,090 --> 01:34:31,430
But they also addressed
that in the study.

2202
01:34:31,430 --> 01:34:32,930
Point I'd like to
make here is quote

2203
01:34:32,930 --> 01:34:34,430
"although people's
minds were more

2204
01:34:34,430 --> 01:34:37,430
likely to wander
to pleasant topics

2205
01:34:37,430 --> 01:34:39,753
than to unpleasant topics"
and there the difference

2206
01:34:39,753 --> 01:34:40,670
is pretty significant.

2207
01:34:40,670 --> 01:34:44,180
People's minds tended to
wander to pleasant topics

2208
01:34:44,180 --> 01:34:48,080
about 43% of the time as
opposed to unpleasant topics

2209
01:34:48,080 --> 01:34:49,910
about 27% of the time.

2210
01:34:49,910 --> 01:34:54,020
Or to neutral topics and the
remaining 31% of samples.

2211
01:34:54,020 --> 01:34:56,300
"People were no
happier when thinking

2212
01:34:56,300 --> 01:35:00,600
about pleasant topics than
about their current activity".

2213
01:35:00,600 --> 01:35:01,620
Think about that.

2214
01:35:01,620 --> 01:35:03,180
"People were no
happier than when

2215
01:35:03,180 --> 01:35:06,250
thinking about pleasant things
then their current activity".

2216
01:35:06,250 --> 01:35:09,600
In fact, the mere focus
on what they were doing

2217
01:35:09,600 --> 01:35:12,970
was more powerful
than anything else,

2218
01:35:12,970 --> 01:35:15,310
even if they didn't enjoy
what they were doing.

2219
01:35:15,310 --> 01:35:17,970
So they go on here to say, quote
"although negative moods are

2220
01:35:17,970 --> 01:35:20,400
known to cause mind
wandering, I now

2221
01:35:20,400 --> 01:35:23,280
see strongly suggested that
mind wandering was generally

2222
01:35:23,280 --> 01:35:25,920
the cause, the
cause, and not merely

2223
01:35:25,920 --> 01:35:28,090
the consequence of unhappiness."

2224
01:35:28,090 --> 01:35:30,090
So there are a lot of
aspects of this study that

2225
01:35:30,090 --> 01:35:31,320
are worth going into.

2226
01:35:31,320 --> 01:35:35,100
But the major takeaway, or the
one that perhaps we should all

2227
01:35:35,100 --> 01:35:37,980
be most concerned with,
is that when we are not

2228
01:35:37,980 --> 01:35:39,660
focused on what we
are doing, we tend

2229
01:35:39,660 --> 01:35:41,880
to be far less happy
than when we are

2230
01:35:41,880 --> 01:35:43,237
focused on what we are doing.

2231
01:35:43,237 --> 01:35:44,820
Even if what we are
doing is something

2232
01:35:44,820 --> 01:35:46,395
that we don't deem
very pleasant.

2233
01:35:46,395 --> 01:35:48,270
And certainly, if we
are engaged in something

2234
01:35:48,270 --> 01:35:50,837
that we consider very pleasant
and we are very focused on,

2235
01:35:50,837 --> 01:35:52,920
well then our levels of
happiness are the highest.

2236
01:35:52,920 --> 01:35:54,120
That's sort of obvious.

2237
01:35:54,120 --> 01:35:57,630
But what this really speaks
to is the tremendous power

2238
01:35:57,630 --> 01:36:01,620
of building our ability to
focus on what we're doing.

2239
01:36:01,620 --> 01:36:03,493
And to stay present
to what we are doing.

2240
01:36:03,493 --> 01:36:05,160
Now this whole notion
of staying present

2241
01:36:05,160 --> 01:36:07,390
is one that itself is a
little bit complicated.

2242
01:36:07,390 --> 01:36:09,930
And in the episode on meditation
I talked a little bit about

2243
01:36:09,930 --> 01:36:11,850
whether or not it's
beneficial to be

2244
01:36:11,850 --> 01:36:15,180
present to our
internal state, or that

2245
01:36:15,180 --> 01:36:17,340
is our inter receptive state.

2246
01:36:17,340 --> 01:36:21,600
Our feelings of our heart
rate and how full or empty

2247
01:36:21,600 --> 01:36:25,350
our gut feels or our state of
being from our skin inward,

2248
01:36:25,350 --> 01:36:26,965
or whether or not
we should focus

2249
01:36:26,965 --> 01:36:29,340
on being present to things in
our immediate surroundings.

2250
01:36:29,340 --> 01:36:30,750
Both our versions
of being quote,

2251
01:36:30,750 --> 01:36:33,100
unquote "present"
as you can imagine.

2252
01:36:33,100 --> 01:36:35,940
But in the one case,
we're focused internally,

2253
01:36:35,940 --> 01:36:37,710
in the other we're
focused externally,

2254
01:36:37,710 --> 01:36:39,210
and of course, most
of the time it's

2255
01:36:39,210 --> 01:36:40,493
some combination of the two.

2256
01:36:40,493 --> 01:36:41,910
But what this study
really says is

2257
01:36:41,910 --> 01:36:45,630
that any practice that can
powerfully impact our ability

2258
01:36:45,630 --> 01:36:49,955
to remain present in the
activity we are engaged in,

2259
01:36:49,955 --> 01:36:51,330
could even be a
phone call, could

2260
01:36:51,330 --> 01:36:54,032
be texting for that matter,
could be social media

2261
01:36:54,032 --> 01:36:54,990
for that matter, right?

2262
01:36:54,990 --> 01:36:57,100
We're not placing judgment
on the activity here.

2263
01:36:57,100 --> 01:36:58,767
In fact, what we're
really talking about

2264
01:36:58,767 --> 01:37:02,040
is the enormous happiness
increasing value

2265
01:37:02,040 --> 01:37:04,680
of being present to what
we're doing regardless

2266
01:37:04,680 --> 01:37:05,880
of what we are doing.

2267
01:37:05,880 --> 01:37:08,940
And a practice that's known to
be beneficial for increasing

2268
01:37:08,940 --> 01:37:12,760
our ability to focus
is, among other things,

2269
01:37:12,760 --> 01:37:15,310
a short meditation practice.

2270
01:37:15,310 --> 01:37:18,120
In fact, work from Wendy
Suzuki's lab at NYU,

2271
01:37:18,120 --> 01:37:20,130
again, Wendy's been a
guest on this podcast.

2272
01:37:20,130 --> 01:37:22,020
Her laboratory has
shown that even

2273
01:37:22,020 --> 01:37:25,110
a very brief meditation
of about 13 minutes,

2274
01:37:25,110 --> 01:37:26,970
and this would be the
sort of quote unquote

2275
01:37:26,970 --> 01:37:29,070
"classic" type of
meditation of eyes

2276
01:37:29,070 --> 01:37:31,020
closed, focusing
on one's breathing.

2277
01:37:31,020 --> 01:37:33,750
Even a very brief meditation
of just 13 minutes

2278
01:37:33,750 --> 01:37:38,310
or so done consistently,
so ideally, every day.

2279
01:37:38,310 --> 01:37:40,900
But I have to imagine that
even if you skip a day,

2280
01:37:40,900 --> 01:37:42,120
there are still benefits.

2281
01:37:42,120 --> 01:37:44,370
That sort of
meditation can greatly

2282
01:37:44,370 --> 01:37:45,990
enhance one's ability to focus.

2283
01:37:45,990 --> 01:37:48,060
In her studies,
that was also shown

2284
01:37:48,060 --> 01:37:52,020
that sort of brief meditation
could also greatly enhance

2285
01:37:52,020 --> 01:37:54,698
mood and sleep and
various aspects

2286
01:37:54,698 --> 01:37:55,740
of cognitive performance.

2287
01:37:55,740 --> 01:37:58,500
And work from my laboratory,
in collaboration with Dr. David

2288
01:37:58,500 --> 01:38:00,990
Spiegel at Stanford,
department of psychiatry

2289
01:38:00,990 --> 01:38:04,210
has shown that even briefer
meditations of even just five

2290
01:38:04,210 --> 01:38:07,620
minutes per day can have fairly
outsized positive effects

2291
01:38:07,620 --> 01:38:09,660
on a number of different
parameters, as well.

2292
01:38:09,660 --> 01:38:12,360
Those very brief
types of meditations,

2293
01:38:12,360 --> 01:38:15,960
because they really are
focusing and more accurately,

2294
01:38:15,960 --> 01:38:18,240
I should say,
refocusing exercises.

2295
01:38:18,240 --> 01:38:21,090
When you do that sort of
activity of closing your eyes

2296
01:38:21,090 --> 01:38:23,610
and forcing yourself
to focus and refocus

2297
01:38:23,610 --> 01:38:25,560
on your breath and
internal state,

2298
01:38:25,560 --> 01:38:27,360
that is directing your
perception inward.

2299
01:38:27,360 --> 01:38:30,390
Or if you choose, you
could deliberately

2300
01:38:30,390 --> 01:38:32,790
focus your perception
on some external object

2301
01:38:32,790 --> 01:38:36,060
or sound, for that matter.

2302
01:38:36,060 --> 01:38:39,720
When one does that, the circuits
of the brain involved in focus

2303
01:38:39,720 --> 01:38:41,490
dramatically improve.

2304
01:38:41,490 --> 01:38:45,300
That is they rewire and
increase their ability for you

2305
01:38:45,300 --> 01:38:47,370
to achieve focus.

2306
01:38:47,370 --> 01:38:49,770
Many of us have heard about
meditation, many of us

2307
01:38:49,770 --> 01:38:53,130
think about meditation as
a "mindfulness" exercise.

2308
01:38:53,130 --> 01:38:55,710
Mindfulness in quotes, because
that itself needs definition.

2309
01:38:55,710 --> 01:38:59,550
But I prefer to view
meditations of the sort

2310
01:38:59,550 --> 01:39:02,700
that I just described
as perceptual or focus

2311
01:39:02,700 --> 01:39:06,480
based training, which is
really what the data point to.

2312
01:39:06,480 --> 01:39:08,460
Notions around consciousness
and states of mind

2313
01:39:08,460 --> 01:39:12,030
are very hard to define, but
it's very clear that even

2314
01:39:12,030 --> 01:39:15,300
a 5 minute a day or ideally,
an up to a 13 minute a day

2315
01:39:15,300 --> 01:39:18,600
meditation can greatly
increase our ability to focus.

2316
01:39:18,600 --> 01:39:21,090
And based on the
findings in this paper,

2317
01:39:21,090 --> 01:39:24,720
"A wandering mind is an unhappy
mind" also make it very clear

2318
01:39:24,720 --> 01:39:28,260
that the ability to
refocus again and again

2319
01:39:28,260 --> 01:39:31,260
and again on what we're
doing throughout our day,

2320
01:39:31,260 --> 01:39:33,240
regardless of what
we're doing, can

2321
01:39:33,240 --> 01:39:37,530
have a very dramatic, in fact,
a statistically significant

2322
01:39:37,530 --> 01:39:40,057
increase on our levels
of overall happiness.

2323
01:39:40,057 --> 01:39:41,640
So what else does
the research tell us

2324
01:39:41,640 --> 01:39:45,360
we can do to increase our
levels of genuine happiness?

2325
01:39:45,360 --> 01:39:48,660
Well, it's very clear based
on the longitudinal study

2326
01:39:48,660 --> 01:39:51,780
from Harvard, as well
as the Yale happiness

2327
01:39:51,780 --> 01:39:55,230
project and the work of
numerous laboratories in the US

2328
01:39:55,230 --> 01:39:59,410
and elsewhere, that
quality social connection

2329
01:39:59,410 --> 01:40:02,860
is extremely powerful
in terms of its ability

2330
01:40:02,860 --> 01:40:05,560
to increase our
levels of happiness.

2331
01:40:05,560 --> 01:40:07,780
What is quality
social connection?

2332
01:40:07,780 --> 01:40:10,750
Quality social connection
falls into a number

2333
01:40:10,750 --> 01:40:11,740
of different bins.

2334
01:40:11,740 --> 01:40:14,770
This can be romantic connection,
this can be friendship,

2335
01:40:14,770 --> 01:40:16,990
this can even be
coworker or just

2336
01:40:16,990 --> 01:40:20,470
daily superficial
interaction type connections.

2337
01:40:20,470 --> 01:40:22,447
That's surprising
to a lot of people,

2338
01:40:22,447 --> 01:40:25,030
because I think a lot of people
hear quality social connection

2339
01:40:25,030 --> 01:40:27,100
and they think
deep conversation.

2340
01:40:27,100 --> 01:40:29,500
But it's very clear
from the research

2341
01:40:29,500 --> 01:40:33,040
that oftentimes our
conversations with people

2342
01:40:33,040 --> 01:40:36,163
that we are closest to are
actually quite shallow.

2343
01:40:36,163 --> 01:40:38,830
If you think about it, if you've
been in a romantic relationship

2344
01:40:38,830 --> 01:40:40,670
or a friendship for a
long period of time,

2345
01:40:40,670 --> 01:40:42,880
or maybe even a sibling
relationship or other family

2346
01:40:42,880 --> 01:40:45,790
relationship, much of
what you talk about

2347
01:40:45,790 --> 01:40:49,730
is fairly superficial
or fairly trivial.

2348
01:40:49,730 --> 01:40:52,330
In fact, it's often a
sharing of the trivial day

2349
01:40:52,330 --> 01:40:55,780
to day things between two
people or through groups

2350
01:40:55,780 --> 01:40:58,300
of people that
leads to the feeling

2351
01:40:58,300 --> 01:41:00,460
that people are really
connected to one another.

2352
01:41:00,460 --> 01:41:03,820
In particular, if it's involving
shared experiences of any kind,

2353
01:41:03,820 --> 01:41:05,480
good or bad.

2354
01:41:05,480 --> 01:41:08,320
So there's an extensive
literature on social connection

2355
01:41:08,320 --> 01:41:09,910
and how to build
social connection.

2356
01:41:09,910 --> 01:41:11,530
This certainly
should be the topic

2357
01:41:11,530 --> 01:41:13,520
of a full episode
of this podcast

2358
01:41:13,520 --> 01:41:15,050
in the not too distant future.

2359
01:41:15,050 --> 01:41:18,340
But because social connection
can have such a powerful impact

2360
01:41:18,340 --> 01:41:21,790
on our states of happiness
and overall well-being,

2361
01:41:21,790 --> 01:41:25,150
I want to emphasize a few
features of social connection

2362
01:41:25,150 --> 01:41:27,400
that I think most people
might not appreciate.

2363
01:41:27,400 --> 01:41:30,140
Once again, when we hear
quality social connection,

2364
01:41:30,140 --> 01:41:32,860
I think most of us tend to
think about deep, meaningful

2365
01:41:32,860 --> 01:41:36,160
conversation or long walks
on the beach or camping trips

2366
01:41:36,160 --> 01:41:37,520
together or travel together.

2367
01:41:37,520 --> 01:41:39,460
And while all of those
certainly qualify

2368
01:41:39,460 --> 01:41:43,240
as wonderful opportunities
for social connection,

2369
01:41:43,240 --> 01:41:45,490
opportunities for
quality social connection

2370
01:41:45,490 --> 01:41:48,530
are certainly not limited to
those kinds of interactions.

2371
01:41:48,530 --> 01:41:52,250
In fact, I can recall times
in my graduate career,

2372
01:41:52,250 --> 01:41:54,880
so this would be times when I
was living in the laboratory.

2373
01:41:54,880 --> 01:41:57,790
Because that was a significant
portion of my graduate years.

2374
01:41:57,790 --> 01:42:01,030
And one of the more important
social connections for me

2375
01:42:01,030 --> 01:42:04,960
was the staff that worked there
in the wee hours of the night

2376
01:42:04,960 --> 01:42:06,890
and that came in very
early in the morning.

2377
01:42:06,890 --> 01:42:09,940
So one of the more regular
social connections I had is I

2378
01:42:09,940 --> 01:42:13,180
would brush my teeth in
the hallway bathroom.

2379
01:42:13,180 --> 01:42:16,040
And there was no one else
really around at that time,

2380
01:42:16,040 --> 01:42:17,830
except for the
janitors that tended

2381
01:42:17,830 --> 01:42:19,480
to leave early in the morning.

2382
01:42:19,480 --> 01:42:21,370
They had worked a good
portion of the night.

2383
01:42:21,370 --> 01:42:23,662
Or that were arriving
very early in the day.

2384
01:42:23,662 --> 01:42:25,870
And the fact that I would
see them on a regular basis

2385
01:42:25,870 --> 01:42:27,670
and maybe exchange a few
words about their work

2386
01:42:27,670 --> 01:42:29,920
or their families or the
holidays, actually for me,

2387
01:42:29,920 --> 01:42:31,420
became very meaningful.

2388
01:42:31,420 --> 01:42:33,820
In part, because my social
connections at the time

2389
01:42:33,820 --> 01:42:36,160
were really limited to
only social connections

2390
01:42:36,160 --> 01:42:38,380
that I had in the
context of work.

2391
01:42:38,380 --> 01:42:41,290
Now some people might look
at my schedule at that time

2392
01:42:41,290 --> 01:42:43,310
and look at my life at
that time and say, well,

2393
01:42:43,310 --> 01:42:44,680
that was very unhealthy.

2394
01:42:44,680 --> 01:42:47,350
You were lacking in
certain number of ways.

2395
01:42:47,350 --> 01:42:49,870
But frankly, looking
back, and at the time,

2396
01:42:49,870 --> 01:42:52,030
and I know this because
I journaled at the time,

2397
01:42:52,030 --> 01:42:53,860
I was exceedingly
happy, at least

2398
01:42:53,860 --> 01:42:55,270
for that stage of my life.

2399
01:42:55,270 --> 01:42:56,860
At that stage of
my life, I wanted

2400
01:42:56,860 --> 01:43:01,600
to be focused primarily on
doing experiments and immersing

2401
01:43:01,600 --> 01:43:03,940
myself in my
scientific training.

2402
01:43:03,940 --> 01:43:07,930
And for me, the even seemingly
insignificant interactions

2403
01:43:07,930 --> 01:43:11,030
of talking to the
janitor in the morning

2404
01:43:11,030 --> 01:43:13,850
or some of the other regular
staff was not insignificant.

2405
01:43:13,850 --> 01:43:15,680
In fact, for me it
was very significant.

2406
01:43:15,680 --> 01:43:17,990
And over the holidays when
their hours were reduced,

2407
01:43:17,990 --> 01:43:19,580
I actually missed
them quite a lot.

2408
01:43:19,580 --> 01:43:21,080
And even as I talk
about this, I can

2409
01:43:21,080 --> 01:43:22,700
recall the feelings
of well-being

2410
01:43:22,700 --> 01:43:24,377
of just seeing familiar faces.

2411
01:43:24,377 --> 01:43:26,210
And that brings up an
important point, which

2412
01:43:26,210 --> 01:43:30,200
is there's quite extensive
literature pointing to the fact

2413
01:43:30,200 --> 01:43:34,370
that when we see faces,
especially faces in the morning

2414
01:43:34,370 --> 01:43:38,750
and in the late afternoon,
there is a positive impact

2415
01:43:38,750 --> 01:43:40,290
on the emotional circuitry.

2416
01:43:40,290 --> 01:43:42,290
Or I should say, the
circuitry of the brain that

2417
01:43:42,290 --> 01:43:44,390
underlies emotional well-being.

2418
01:43:44,390 --> 01:43:46,430
And that shouldn't
come as surprising.

2419
01:43:46,430 --> 01:43:50,150
We as old world primates,
much like other primates,

2420
01:43:50,150 --> 01:43:53,810
are very dependent on faces
and facial expressions

2421
01:43:53,810 --> 01:43:57,330
in terms of registering
our own place in life

2422
01:43:57,330 --> 01:43:59,210
and our emotional state.

2423
01:43:59,210 --> 01:44:00,950
Now the origins
of this are many.

2424
01:44:00,950 --> 01:44:03,440
In particular, we
have a brain area,

2425
01:44:03,440 --> 01:44:05,425
it's actually called
the fusiform face gyrus.

2426
01:44:05,425 --> 01:44:06,800
This is an area
of the brain that

2427
01:44:06,800 --> 01:44:09,380
was largely
discovered by a woman

2428
01:44:09,380 --> 01:44:11,510
by Nancy Kanwisher at MIT.

2429
01:44:11,510 --> 01:44:14,360
And the Kanwisher lab
has done extensive work

2430
01:44:14,360 --> 01:44:16,760
showing that this
brain area that's

2431
01:44:16,760 --> 01:44:21,410
dedicated to the processing
of faces, and not just faces

2432
01:44:21,410 --> 01:44:24,470
in real life, but faces
on computer screens

2433
01:44:24,470 --> 01:44:27,200
and elsewhere, are
intimately tied

2434
01:44:27,200 --> 01:44:29,780
to areas of the brain that are
associated with emotionality.

2435
01:44:29,780 --> 01:44:31,738
That's actually a work
from another laboratory,

2436
01:44:31,738 --> 01:44:34,190
Dorsal's laboratory at
Caltech, now at Uc Berkeley,

2437
01:44:34,190 --> 01:44:36,380
has shown that this
face processing

2438
01:44:36,380 --> 01:44:41,240
area in the brain in both
non-human primates and primates

2439
01:44:41,240 --> 01:44:44,660
is directly linked to
the areas of our brain

2440
01:44:44,660 --> 01:44:47,180
that associate with
anxiety and fear.

2441
01:44:47,180 --> 01:44:48,590
But also, areas
of the brain that

2442
01:44:48,590 --> 01:44:50,030
are associated with well-being.

2443
01:44:50,030 --> 01:44:51,770
So it comes as no
surprise that when

2444
01:44:51,770 --> 01:44:53,990
we see faces, in
particular, friendly faces,

2445
01:44:53,990 --> 01:44:56,780
even if we have just brief
interactions with those faces,

2446
01:44:56,780 --> 01:44:58,970
and even if no
words are exchanged,

2447
01:44:58,970 --> 01:45:01,430
that creates the
sense of social bond.

2448
01:45:01,430 --> 01:45:03,650
And it creates a sense
of predictability.

2449
01:45:03,650 --> 01:45:05,900
And I raise this again because
I think a lot of people

2450
01:45:05,900 --> 01:45:07,610
think that social
connection always

2451
01:45:07,610 --> 01:45:10,630
has to come in the form of
close friendships, which

2452
01:45:10,630 --> 01:45:11,630
of course are wonderful.

2453
01:45:11,630 --> 01:45:14,030
Or close romantic relationships,
which of course, are wonderful.

2454
01:45:14,030 --> 01:45:16,770
Or close family relationships,
which of course, are wonderful.

2455
01:45:16,770 --> 01:45:20,480
But as we'll soon discuss
in our model of happiness,

2456
01:45:20,480 --> 01:45:22,070
or how to achieve
happiness based

2457
01:45:22,070 --> 01:45:25,790
on the scientific
literature in a few minutes,

2458
01:45:25,790 --> 01:45:29,720
social connection can and
should come in various forms.

2459
01:45:29,720 --> 01:45:31,640
And when I say
various forms, I mean

2460
01:45:31,640 --> 01:45:35,480
forms of brief interaction,
more superficial interaction,

2461
01:45:35,480 --> 01:45:38,060
and forms of deeper interaction.

2462
01:45:38,060 --> 01:45:40,520
All of those are relevant
to our states of happiness.

2463
01:45:40,520 --> 01:45:43,850
And there's research to
support that daily interactions

2464
01:45:43,850 --> 01:45:47,900
with somebody at a cafe or
just a brief hello or a smile.

2465
01:45:47,900 --> 01:45:50,060
Provided that we
are both present,

2466
01:45:50,060 --> 01:45:53,070
or we make the effort to be
present to those interactions,

2467
01:45:53,070 --> 01:45:55,940
however brief they are,
can have a positive effect

2468
01:45:55,940 --> 01:45:57,260
on people's overall well-being.

2469
01:45:57,260 --> 01:46:00,470
And not just in that
moment, but consistently.

2470
01:46:00,470 --> 01:46:02,210
Evidenced by the
fact, I think, that

2471
01:46:02,210 --> 01:46:04,340
when I look back on
those years of working

2472
01:46:04,340 --> 01:46:08,270
long hours in the laboratory and
essentially restricting myself

2473
01:46:08,270 --> 01:46:12,680
either to exercising,
sleeping, eating or working.

2474
01:46:12,680 --> 01:46:15,170
Again, that's what I wanted
at that stage of my life.

2475
01:46:15,170 --> 01:46:16,920
Certainly, not the way
I live my life now.

2476
01:46:16,920 --> 01:46:19,080
But that's what I wanted
that stage of my life.

2477
01:46:19,080 --> 01:46:21,410
That even those
seemingly insignificant

2478
01:46:21,410 --> 01:46:24,230
social interactions
were important to me

2479
01:46:24,230 --> 01:46:26,690
and had a potent
impact on increasing

2480
01:46:26,690 --> 01:46:27,620
my level of happiness.

2481
01:46:27,620 --> 01:46:28,770
And frankly, still do.

2482
01:46:28,770 --> 01:46:30,380
And I feel that right now.

2483
01:46:30,380 --> 01:46:33,980
That said, I think all of us
can appreciate the immense value

2484
01:46:33,980 --> 01:46:38,090
of social connection that is of
the more long lasting, and for

2485
01:46:38,090 --> 01:46:39,930
lack of a better
word, richer type,

2486
01:46:39,930 --> 01:46:43,250
whether or not that is with
siblings or with parents

2487
01:46:43,250 --> 01:46:45,920
or with friends or
with romantic partners.

2488
01:46:45,920 --> 01:46:48,320
For that reason, I want
to emphasize a little bit

2489
01:46:48,320 --> 01:46:50,780
about what
constitutes connection

2490
01:46:50,780 --> 01:46:52,430
and what constitutes
social connection.

2491
01:46:52,430 --> 01:46:54,560
There are basically two
forms of social connection

2492
01:46:54,560 --> 01:46:57,110
that have been studied
and I'll review both,

2493
01:46:57,110 --> 01:46:59,600
as it relates to increasing
our levels of happiness.

2494
01:46:59,600 --> 01:47:02,480
And the first one is
presence and eye contact,

2495
01:47:02,480 --> 01:47:04,680
and the second is
physical contact.

2496
01:47:04,680 --> 01:47:06,710
So in terms of presence
and eye contact

2497
01:47:06,710 --> 01:47:08,840
there's been a lot
of studies about

2498
01:47:08,840 --> 01:47:11,900
whether or not people
exchange direct eye contact

2499
01:47:11,900 --> 01:47:15,230
during conversation or not,
dictating whether or not

2500
01:47:15,230 --> 01:47:18,380
each individual in
that interaction

2501
01:47:18,380 --> 01:47:21,050
feels as if they
had a connection.

2502
01:47:21,050 --> 01:47:24,230
Now again, keep in mind that
while we think of connection

2503
01:47:24,230 --> 01:47:26,870
as relating to some deep
or meaningful conversation,

2504
01:47:26,870 --> 01:47:28,370
and oftentimes that
can be the case.

2505
01:47:28,370 --> 01:47:32,990
Think for instance, an excellent
therapist patient relationship.

2506
01:47:32,990 --> 01:47:35,180
Or an excellent
romantic relationship.

2507
01:47:35,180 --> 01:47:38,300
Or an excellent friendship
where you really feel

2508
01:47:38,300 --> 01:47:40,460
heard and understood, or
at least to the extent

2509
01:47:40,460 --> 01:47:42,190
that people are
willing to explore

2510
01:47:42,190 --> 01:47:43,190
certain topics with you.

2511
01:47:43,190 --> 01:47:45,065
You're willing to hear
them and listen really

2512
01:47:45,065 --> 01:47:46,482
carefully for what
they're saying,

2513
01:47:46,482 --> 01:47:49,040
and they're willing to hear and
listen to what you're saying

2514
01:47:49,040 --> 01:47:50,570
in an attempt to understand.

2515
01:47:50,570 --> 01:47:53,060
That certainly can enhance
the sense of social connection

2516
01:47:53,060 --> 01:47:55,940
leading to what people would
call social bonds leading

2517
01:47:55,940 --> 01:47:57,410
to increased happiness.

2518
01:47:57,410 --> 01:48:02,030
But eye contact is also known
to be an important feature.

2519
01:48:02,030 --> 01:48:04,130
The thing about eye
contact is that most people

2520
01:48:04,130 --> 01:48:06,440
assume that a lot
of eye contact,

2521
01:48:06,440 --> 01:48:08,420
and in fact,
ongoing eye contact,

2522
01:48:08,420 --> 01:48:11,570
is critical to a
sense of connection.

2523
01:48:11,570 --> 01:48:13,250
And in fact, that's
not the case.

2524
01:48:13,250 --> 01:48:16,577
There's a recent paper that I
find really interesting that

2525
01:48:16,577 --> 01:48:18,410
was published in
Proceedings of the National

2526
01:48:18,410 --> 01:48:21,140
Academy of Sciences in 2021.

2527
01:48:21,140 --> 01:48:23,330
The title of this
paper is "Eye contact

2528
01:48:23,330 --> 01:48:25,640
marks the rise and fall
of shared attention

2529
01:48:25,640 --> 01:48:26,670
in conversation".

2530
01:48:26,670 --> 01:48:28,920
I find this paper interesting
for a number of reasons.

2531
01:48:28,920 --> 01:48:31,790
First of all, my laboratory
works on internal states

2532
01:48:31,790 --> 01:48:33,380
and vision, so it
relates directly

2533
01:48:33,380 --> 01:48:35,210
to the work that
my laboratory does.

2534
01:48:35,210 --> 01:48:37,970
But also, that it
violates what I thought

2535
01:48:37,970 --> 01:48:40,490
was a general rule of
social connection, which

2536
01:48:40,490 --> 01:48:42,980
is this idea that two people
needed to be focused on one

2537
01:48:42,980 --> 01:48:45,230
another, that is
looking at one another

2538
01:48:45,230 --> 01:48:48,740
directly and fairly consistently
throughout a conversation

2539
01:48:48,740 --> 01:48:51,170
in order for the feeling
of connection to emerge.

2540
01:48:51,170 --> 01:48:53,335
But it turns out
that's not the case.

2541
01:48:53,335 --> 01:48:55,460
And in fact, just to give
you the takeaway and then

2542
01:48:55,460 --> 01:49:00,290
I'll flesh it out a little bit
with some data, eye contact,

2543
01:49:00,290 --> 01:49:03,448
or I should say mutual
eye contact, so two people

2544
01:49:03,448 --> 01:49:05,990
registering the presence of the
other person looking at them.

2545
01:49:05,990 --> 01:49:07,640
You're looking at me
and I'm looking at you.

2546
01:49:07,640 --> 01:49:09,098
If you're watching
this on YouTube,

2547
01:49:09,098 --> 01:49:12,223
then perhaps we are actually
doing this at that moment.

2548
01:49:12,223 --> 01:49:13,640
And if you're
listening, just know

2549
01:49:13,640 --> 01:49:15,050
that I'm looking
directly into the camera

2550
01:49:15,050 --> 01:49:16,467
as I'm saying this
at this moment.

2551
01:49:16,467 --> 01:49:19,820
If we were to be looking
directly at one another,

2552
01:49:19,820 --> 01:49:23,640
that, it turns out,
signals the next step,

2553
01:49:23,640 --> 01:49:27,290
which is that it's very likely
that we will each both look

2554
01:49:27,290 --> 01:49:28,350
away.

2555
01:49:28,350 --> 01:49:31,490
And that turns out to
be a way in which we set

2556
01:49:31,490 --> 01:49:35,083
and reset attention continually
during conversation.

2557
01:49:35,083 --> 01:49:36,500
So again, I really
like this study

2558
01:49:36,500 --> 01:49:38,730
because of the high fidelity.

2559
01:49:38,730 --> 01:49:40,520
The high temporal precision.

2560
01:49:40,520 --> 01:49:42,770
That is, the precision
over time at which they

2561
01:49:42,770 --> 01:49:48,020
looked at eye contact and
engagement of attention

2562
01:49:48,020 --> 01:49:49,340
between individuals.

2563
01:49:49,340 --> 01:49:51,955
And they did this by looking
at things like pupil size

2564
01:49:51,955 --> 01:49:53,330
and of course
where the eyes were

2565
01:49:53,330 --> 01:49:54,665
looking and so on and so forth.

2566
01:49:54,665 --> 01:49:56,790
The basic takeaway of this
study was the following.

2567
01:49:56,790 --> 01:49:58,290
And here I'm quoting
from the study.

2568
01:49:58,290 --> 01:50:01,490
Quote "Rather than
maximizing shared attention,

2569
01:50:01,490 --> 01:50:03,770
good conversation
may require shifts

2570
01:50:03,770 --> 01:50:07,520
in and out of shared states
accompanied by eye contact".

2571
01:50:07,520 --> 01:50:10,610
So what this basically
says is that when

2572
01:50:10,610 --> 01:50:13,125
two people are
involved in a very,

2573
01:50:13,125 --> 01:50:14,750
let's call it an
intimate conversation,

2574
01:50:14,750 --> 01:50:17,690
but the word intimate
should not be misconstrued

2575
01:50:17,690 --> 01:50:20,330
to mean something about
intimacy or sexual intimacy

2576
01:50:20,330 --> 01:50:21,710
or physical intimacy.

2577
01:50:21,710 --> 01:50:23,990
Just a conversation
in which both people

2578
01:50:23,990 --> 01:50:27,320
feel present to the
conversation and focused

2579
01:50:27,320 --> 01:50:30,020
on that conversation and that
conversation and its contents

2580
01:50:30,020 --> 01:50:30,950
only.

2581
01:50:30,950 --> 01:50:33,840
The tendency is for people
to take turns talking,

2582
01:50:33,840 --> 01:50:35,840
although sometimes,
depending on the individuals

2583
01:50:35,840 --> 01:50:37,580
they might interrupt
more or less.

2584
01:50:37,580 --> 01:50:40,370
Again, interrupting can
be a sign of interest,

2585
01:50:40,370 --> 01:50:42,630
it doesn't always have
to be rude, by the way.

2586
01:50:42,630 --> 01:50:45,290
But they're sharing information.

2587
01:50:45,290 --> 01:50:48,500
Hopefully, about a common
topic or set of topics.

2588
01:50:48,500 --> 01:50:51,503
They will at some moment
look at one another.

2589
01:50:51,503 --> 01:50:52,670
That's what the study shows.

2590
01:50:52,670 --> 01:50:55,700
And that after briefly
gazing directly at one

2591
01:50:55,700 --> 01:50:59,810
another, attention peaks,
and then they will look away,

2592
01:50:59,810 --> 01:51:01,670
and attention will get reduced.

2593
01:51:01,670 --> 01:51:03,740
And then the
conversation consists

2594
01:51:03,740 --> 01:51:08,510
of a series of focusing back
on one another with their eyes,

2595
01:51:08,510 --> 01:51:10,940
and then focusing off,
focusing on and focusing off.

2596
01:51:10,940 --> 01:51:13,940
And those mutual
eye contact moments

2597
01:51:13,940 --> 01:51:16,730
actually predict the
breaking of attention.

2598
01:51:16,730 --> 01:51:18,858
So it's this ramping up
of attention and braking

2599
01:51:18,858 --> 01:51:19,400
of attention.

2600
01:51:19,400 --> 01:51:21,560
Ramping of attention and
braking of attention.

2601
01:51:21,560 --> 01:51:23,960
I think these are important
results because they violate

2602
01:51:23,960 --> 01:51:27,680
this stereotype or assumption
that deep social connection

2603
01:51:27,680 --> 01:51:31,040
of the sort leading
to happiness always

2604
01:51:31,040 --> 01:51:35,180
involves ongoing eye
contact or ongoing focus.

2605
01:51:35,180 --> 01:51:39,650
Just as with meditation, just
as with any activity, frankly,

2606
01:51:39,650 --> 01:51:43,580
we undergo shifts in
attention and focus.

2607
01:51:43,580 --> 01:51:46,550
That is focus ramps up and
then it breaks, and then

2608
01:51:46,550 --> 01:51:47,240
it re-engages.

2609
01:51:47,240 --> 01:51:49,880
It ramps up it breaks,
and then it re-engages.

2610
01:51:49,880 --> 01:51:52,280
And that, it turns
out, is the basis

2611
01:51:52,280 --> 01:51:55,170
of in-depth connected
conversation.

2612
01:51:55,170 --> 01:51:57,650
So for those of you that
are interested in creating

2613
01:51:57,650 --> 01:52:01,110
social connection
in any context,

2614
01:52:01,110 --> 01:52:04,020
and in particular for sake
of increasing happiness,

2615
01:52:04,020 --> 01:52:06,750
because it's very clear
that social connections,

2616
01:52:06,750 --> 01:52:09,390
even if they are fairly
superficial social connections,

2617
01:52:09,390 --> 01:52:11,340
can increase our
sense of happiness.

2618
01:52:11,340 --> 01:52:13,290
Seeing faces is important.

2619
01:52:13,290 --> 01:52:16,080
Ideally, faces in person,
although I suppose these days,

2620
01:52:16,080 --> 01:52:19,530
over Zoom or over other
screen type medium

2621
01:52:19,530 --> 01:52:21,610
would be a close second.

2622
01:52:21,610 --> 01:52:25,470
But the point is that if you
want to increase happiness

2623
01:52:25,470 --> 01:52:27,303
you need to have quality
social connections.

2624
01:52:27,303 --> 01:52:29,387
And if you want to have
quality social connections

2625
01:52:29,387 --> 01:52:31,053
you need to be
present and engage

2626
01:52:31,053 --> 01:52:32,220
in those social connections.

2627
01:52:32,220 --> 01:52:36,330
And that requires a viewing
of each other's faces,

2628
01:52:36,330 --> 01:52:39,420
ideally, which is not to say
that a phone call or text

2629
01:52:39,420 --> 01:52:41,140
exchange can't be meaningful.

2630
01:52:41,140 --> 01:52:44,070
But that faces are really
the most powerful way

2631
01:52:44,070 --> 01:52:45,990
to engage in social contact.

2632
01:52:45,990 --> 01:52:49,560
And that eye contact, not
consistent eye contact,

2633
01:52:49,560 --> 01:52:52,080
but eye contact of the sort
that builds up and then breaks

2634
01:52:52,080 --> 01:52:54,090
and builds up and breaks
across the interaction

2635
01:52:54,090 --> 01:52:59,460
is going to be the best way
that we are aware of to feel

2636
01:52:59,460 --> 01:53:01,410
that one had a real connection.

2637
01:53:01,410 --> 01:53:02,910
This should also
remove any pressure

2638
01:53:02,910 --> 01:53:05,580
that you might feel to
constantly look at somebody

2639
01:53:05,580 --> 01:53:08,095
or to be completely eyes
open staring at them

2640
01:53:08,095 --> 01:53:10,470
without blinking or diverting
your attention at any point

2641
01:53:10,470 --> 01:53:11,850
during a conversation.

2642
01:53:11,850 --> 01:53:14,070
This also frankly,
is an opportunity

2643
01:53:14,070 --> 01:53:17,610
where if somebody says, hey,
you're not paying attention

2644
01:53:17,610 --> 01:53:20,670
because you look away,
that you may actually

2645
01:53:20,670 --> 01:53:22,860
be engaging in what is
the more typical form

2646
01:53:22,860 --> 01:53:23,910
of healthy connection.

2647
01:53:23,910 --> 01:53:26,693
I talked about this long ago
on an episode about focus.

2648
01:53:26,693 --> 01:53:28,110
It turns out when
we are listening

2649
01:53:28,110 --> 01:53:29,872
very intently to
somebody and trying

2650
01:53:29,872 --> 01:53:31,830
to remember the information
they're telling us,

2651
01:53:31,830 --> 01:53:33,332
we will often close our eyes.

2652
01:53:33,332 --> 01:53:35,790
And that's not a form of lack
of attention, that's actually

2653
01:53:35,790 --> 01:53:37,050
a form of attending in.

2654
01:53:37,050 --> 01:53:40,410
Because we have so much of
our brain devoted to vision.

2655
01:53:40,410 --> 01:53:42,870
When 40% of our brain
is devoted to vision

2656
01:53:42,870 --> 01:53:44,890
in some way or another,
when we close our eyes,

2657
01:53:44,890 --> 01:53:47,280
we can actually devote
more attentional resources

2658
01:53:47,280 --> 01:53:50,250
to remembering the specifics
of what people are telling us.

2659
01:53:50,250 --> 01:53:52,620
But again, please don't
go through conversations

2660
01:53:52,620 --> 01:53:54,310
with your eyes closed
the entire time.

2661
01:53:54,310 --> 01:53:57,390
I think that would certainly
not be conducive to building

2662
01:53:57,390 --> 01:53:58,330
social connection.

2663
01:53:58,330 --> 01:54:01,710
So we know that faces are
important for social connection

2664
01:54:01,710 --> 01:54:04,290
as it relates to
synthetic happiness.

2665
01:54:04,290 --> 01:54:07,320
And we know that eye contact is
really important for building

2666
01:54:07,320 --> 01:54:09,670
social connection.

2667
01:54:09,670 --> 01:54:12,520
Physical contact
is also important

2668
01:54:12,520 --> 01:54:13,540
for social connection.

2669
01:54:13,540 --> 01:54:17,000
And not just romantic or
sexual type connection.

2670
01:54:17,000 --> 01:54:19,480
In fact, there is a form
of physical connection

2671
01:54:19,480 --> 01:54:22,840
that is present
in other primates.

2672
01:54:22,840 --> 01:54:25,960
In fact, it's present as far
as we know, in all mammals.

2673
01:54:25,960 --> 01:54:31,060
And is also very much a feature
of the human nervous system.

2674
01:54:31,060 --> 01:54:32,868
And that's something
called allogrooming.

2675
01:54:32,868 --> 01:54:34,660
I have to imagine that
most people probably

2676
01:54:34,660 --> 01:54:36,077
haven't heard of allogrooming.

2677
01:54:36,077 --> 01:54:37,660
The reason I'm
bringing up alogrooming

2678
01:54:37,660 --> 01:54:41,080
is that it stems from a
fairly extensive literature

2679
01:54:41,080 --> 01:54:45,310
about the prosocial,
pro happiness

2680
01:54:45,310 --> 01:54:47,783
effects of pets on humans.

2681
01:54:47,783 --> 01:54:49,450
In fact, if you want
to read up on this,

2682
01:54:49,450 --> 01:54:52,810
there is a paper out of Yale
University on this topic

2683
01:54:52,810 --> 01:54:53,980
that was published in 2018.

2684
01:54:53,980 --> 01:54:56,313
The title of the paper is
"The influence of interactions

2685
01:54:56,313 --> 01:55:00,368
with dogs on affect", OK
emotion, "anxety and arousal

2686
01:55:00,368 --> 01:55:00,910
in children".

2687
01:55:00,910 --> 01:55:02,570
And it references
some other studies

2688
01:55:02,570 --> 01:55:03,820
that were performed on humans.

2689
01:55:03,820 --> 01:55:07,270
And the basic takeaway is
that these so-called AAAs,

2690
01:55:07,270 --> 01:55:12,010
animal assisted activities,
represent a really potent way

2691
01:55:12,010 --> 01:55:15,430
to increase people,
including children's feelings

2692
01:55:15,430 --> 01:55:16,210
of well-being.

2693
01:55:16,210 --> 01:55:18,580
Now what's interesting
about this to me

2694
01:55:18,580 --> 01:55:22,000
is that dogs
themselves don't really

2695
01:55:22,000 --> 01:55:25,990
have to do much except be
present in the room in order

2696
01:55:25,990 --> 01:55:29,860
for these positive effects, that
is, the reductions in anxiety,

2697
01:55:29,860 --> 01:55:32,200
increases in happiness,
et cetera, to occur.

2698
01:55:32,200 --> 01:55:34,317
And in fact, they can
be very, very brief.

2699
01:55:34,317 --> 01:55:36,400
As they describe in the
paper, "brief unstructured

2700
01:55:36,400 --> 01:55:38,140
interactions with
an unfamiliar dog",

2701
01:55:38,140 --> 01:55:40,030
so you don't even
need to know this dog,

2702
01:55:40,030 --> 01:55:43,300
"after exposure to a moderate
stressor showed higher positive

2703
01:55:43,300 --> 01:55:46,690
affect relevant to participants
who received a soothing object

2704
01:55:46,690 --> 01:55:48,530
or waited for the
same amount of time."

2705
01:55:48,530 --> 01:55:52,240
So just even seeing a dog
for a brief amount of time

2706
01:55:52,240 --> 01:55:56,260
has been shown to reduce
stress and improve happiness,

2707
01:55:56,260 --> 01:55:57,910
or I should say,
increase feelings

2708
01:55:57,910 --> 01:56:01,660
of happiness
overall then a child

2709
01:56:01,660 --> 01:56:03,293
receiving a soothing object.

2710
01:56:03,293 --> 01:56:05,710
Which was, at least for me, a
little bit counterintuitive.

2711
01:56:05,710 --> 01:56:07,030
I would have thought
that children receiving

2712
01:56:07,030 --> 01:56:08,405
a soothing object
would have been

2713
01:56:08,405 --> 01:56:10,760
the more powerful stimulus.

2714
01:56:10,760 --> 01:56:13,198
But in fact, it wasn't, at
least not in this study.

2715
01:56:13,198 --> 01:56:15,490
The real question I think we
should be asking ourselves

2716
01:56:15,490 --> 01:56:18,520
is, what is it about
interactions with others

2717
01:56:18,520 --> 01:56:21,220
and with other animals
that could potentially

2718
01:56:21,220 --> 01:56:24,950
have this prosocial
happiness enhancing effect?

2719
01:56:24,950 --> 01:56:27,100
And the reason I
raise this is also

2720
01:56:27,100 --> 01:56:31,660
because I think many people
are interested in either owning

2721
01:56:31,660 --> 01:56:33,992
or having interactions with
pets as a way to improve

2722
01:56:33,992 --> 01:56:35,200
their feelings of well-being.

2723
01:56:35,200 --> 01:56:38,350
And I say having
interactions with because I

2724
01:56:38,350 --> 01:56:40,840
myself am a good example
of somebody who wasn't

2725
01:56:40,840 --> 01:56:43,183
always able to have pets.

2726
01:56:43,183 --> 01:56:45,100
So when I was a graduate
student in a postdoc,

2727
01:56:45,100 --> 01:56:46,672
I very much wanted a dog.

2728
01:56:46,672 --> 01:56:48,130
Very, very, very
much wanted a dog.

2729
01:56:48,130 --> 01:56:50,297
In fact, there was a rule
in my family at some point

2730
01:56:50,297 --> 01:56:53,172
that I wasn't allowed to talk
about dogs anymore because I

2731
01:56:53,172 --> 01:56:54,880
was talking about all
the breeds of dogs.

2732
01:56:54,880 --> 01:56:58,270
Going to dog breeders,
examining different breeds,

2733
01:56:58,270 --> 01:57:00,310
going to the pound, et cetera.

2734
01:57:00,310 --> 01:57:03,430
The point was that I was
obsessed with getting a dog,

2735
01:57:03,430 --> 01:57:05,800
but I knew I wasn't in a good
position to own a dog yet.

2736
01:57:05,800 --> 01:57:08,300
I didn't have the finances, I
didn't have the correct living

2737
01:57:08,300 --> 01:57:10,270
situation and so on.

2738
01:57:10,270 --> 01:57:12,335
Eventually, I did
own a dog, of course.

2739
01:57:12,335 --> 01:57:13,460
But at the time I couldn't.

2740
01:57:13,460 --> 01:57:15,952
So what I would do is every
Sunday I would go to a place

2741
01:57:15,952 --> 01:57:18,160
where they fostered dogs
and they needed dog walkers.

2742
01:57:18,160 --> 01:57:19,285
And I would walk their dog.

2743
01:57:19,285 --> 01:57:22,330
I would also walk
my neighbor's dogs.

2744
01:57:22,330 --> 01:57:23,540
I didn't charge them for it.

2745
01:57:23,540 --> 01:57:26,140
In fact, I felt like I was
being paid by getting time

2746
01:57:26,140 --> 01:57:27,040
with those dogs.

2747
01:57:27,040 --> 01:57:29,500
And in fact, I put an ad
at that time on Craigslist

2748
01:57:29,500 --> 01:57:31,570
that I would walk
people's dogs for free,

2749
01:57:31,570 --> 01:57:33,490
and only a few people
took that seriously.

2750
01:57:33,490 --> 01:57:36,400
But of the ones that did,
I had a great little cadre

2751
01:57:36,400 --> 01:57:38,920
of dog owners that would allow
me to take their dogs out

2752
01:57:38,920 --> 01:57:40,030
and I was super happy.

2753
01:57:40,030 --> 01:57:41,930
It just made me
very, very happy.

2754
01:57:41,930 --> 01:57:44,170
And I really enjoyed it.

2755
01:57:44,170 --> 01:57:47,230
And frankly, it was a
great opportunity for me

2756
01:57:47,230 --> 01:57:50,080
to also get to the various dog
breeds and the different dog

2757
01:57:50,080 --> 01:57:52,990
temperaments and to learn a bit
about my ability to interact

2758
01:57:52,990 --> 01:57:54,613
with dogs in a certain way.

2759
01:57:54,613 --> 01:57:56,530
I actually got to be a
pretty good dog walker.

2760
01:57:56,530 --> 01:57:57,910
Unfortunately, later
I got a bulldog.

2761
01:57:57,910 --> 01:57:58,960
And it turns out
no matter how good

2762
01:57:58,960 --> 01:58:01,940
a dog walker you are, Bulldogs
just simply don't like to walk.

2763
01:58:01,940 --> 01:58:04,000
In fact, if you've ever
walked up to a bulldog

2764
01:58:04,000 --> 01:58:06,550
and you've offered to
scratch or pet that dog,

2765
01:58:06,550 --> 01:58:08,600
you'll notice that
Bulldogs love that.

2766
01:58:08,600 --> 01:58:11,800
And I would argue, having
been a bulldog owner,

2767
01:58:11,800 --> 01:58:14,410
that they like it because it's
an opportunity for them to stop

2768
01:58:14,410 --> 01:58:14,988
moving.

2769
01:58:14,988 --> 01:58:16,780
But that's more about
the bulldog than what

2770
01:58:16,780 --> 01:58:18,155
I'm about to tell
you next, which

2771
01:58:18,155 --> 01:58:21,190
is this principle of
so-called allogrooming.

2772
01:58:21,190 --> 01:58:23,140
Allogrooming is a
pattern of behavior

2773
01:58:23,140 --> 01:58:26,980
that's observed in essentially
all mammals but very strongly

2774
01:58:26,980 --> 01:58:29,980
in nonhuman primates
and primates,

2775
01:58:29,980 --> 01:58:36,260
where individuals within a
species touch one another.

2776
01:58:36,260 --> 01:58:37,930
And this is non-sexual touch.

2777
01:58:37,930 --> 01:58:42,250
So this would be someone
brushing somebody else's hair

2778
01:58:42,250 --> 01:58:45,680
or combing their hair or even
using a lint roller on them,

2779
01:58:45,680 --> 01:58:46,580
for instance.

2780
01:58:46,580 --> 01:58:49,660
Or someone grooming
somebody else.

2781
01:58:49,660 --> 01:58:52,330
Now typically, one needs
to have an established

2782
01:58:52,330 --> 01:58:53,660
relationship with this person.

2783
01:58:53,660 --> 01:58:55,420
So it could be a professional
type relationship

2784
01:58:55,420 --> 01:58:57,128
where this is a barber
cutting somebody's

2785
01:58:57,128 --> 01:59:01,612
hair or a hairdresser cutting
or styling somebody's hair.

2786
01:59:01,612 --> 01:59:03,070
It could be somebody
giving someone

2787
01:59:03,070 --> 01:59:04,510
a manicure or a pedicure.

2788
01:59:04,510 --> 01:59:06,940
Could be somebody doing skin
care or massage for somebody

2789
01:59:06,940 --> 01:59:08,440
in a professional context.

2790
01:59:08,440 --> 01:59:10,810
Or it could be two
people who have agreed

2791
01:59:10,810 --> 01:59:13,205
that it is appropriate
for the context

2792
01:59:13,205 --> 01:59:14,830
and for the relationship
for one person

2793
01:59:14,830 --> 01:59:17,110
to be grooming somebody else.

2794
01:59:17,110 --> 01:59:19,600
Can even, believe it or not
there's literature on this,

2795
01:59:19,600 --> 01:59:22,930
can even extend into
the realm of people

2796
01:59:22,930 --> 01:59:25,210
sort of cleaning and
picking off other people.

2797
01:59:25,210 --> 01:59:27,580
Now when we see
this in primates,

2798
01:59:27,580 --> 01:59:31,820
it seems like a very cute and
sort of almost understandable

2799
01:59:31,820 --> 01:59:32,320
behavior.

2800
01:59:32,320 --> 01:59:33,850
We can see these
pictures online.

2801
01:59:33,850 --> 01:59:36,100
If you look them up, you can
just look up allogrooming

2802
01:59:36,100 --> 01:59:38,380
and you'll see vast
number of pictures

2803
01:59:38,380 --> 01:59:40,660
of for instance, baboons
picking little things out

2804
01:59:40,660 --> 01:59:42,520
of each other's hair.

2805
01:59:42,520 --> 01:59:46,610
Or grooming and kind of
perusing one another,

2806
01:59:46,610 --> 01:59:49,530
to find things,
presumably parasites

2807
01:59:49,530 --> 01:59:51,280
or like little bits
of plants or something

2808
01:59:51,280 --> 01:59:52,947
like that they want
to remove from them.

2809
01:59:52,947 --> 01:59:55,870
Allogrooming is
known to stimulate

2810
01:59:55,870 --> 01:59:59,510
a certain category of neurons
called the C tactile fibers.

2811
01:59:59,510 --> 02:00:02,620
These are a particular category
of so-called sensory neurons

2812
02:00:02,620 --> 02:00:03,890
that innervate our skin.

2813
02:00:03,890 --> 02:00:06,880
So these are literally like
little endings of neurons,

2814
02:00:06,880 --> 02:00:09,010
little wires that
end up in the skin,

2815
02:00:09,010 --> 02:00:11,470
that when they are
touched lightly

2816
02:00:11,470 --> 02:00:14,302
tend to create a
feeling of well-being

2817
02:00:14,302 --> 02:00:15,760
in the person that's
being touched.

2818
02:00:15,760 --> 02:00:17,710
Again, this is
consensual touch that's

2819
02:00:17,710 --> 02:00:19,300
very context appropriate.

2820
02:00:19,300 --> 02:00:22,360
But it's known to
increase levels

2821
02:00:22,360 --> 02:00:26,210
of oxytocin, a kind of hormone
slash neurotransmitter.

2822
02:00:26,210 --> 02:00:27,460
It's both, really.

2823
02:00:27,460 --> 02:00:31,060
That is known to evoke
feelings of bond.

2824
02:00:31,060 --> 02:00:34,240
Or of feeling bonded to
somebody or something.

2825
02:00:34,240 --> 02:00:36,610
And for many people
we hear about oxytocin

2826
02:00:36,610 --> 02:00:40,050
and we think about the bond
between parent and child,

2827
02:00:40,050 --> 02:00:41,800
in particular mother
and infant where it's

2828
02:00:41,800 --> 02:00:43,060
been most extensively studied.

2829
02:00:43,060 --> 02:00:45,580
Or between two members
of a romantic couple.

2830
02:00:45,580 --> 02:00:47,840
But if you look at the
literature on allogrooming,

2831
02:00:47,840 --> 02:00:50,950
what you find is that when
humans groom one another,

2832
02:00:50,950 --> 02:00:54,430
the increases in oxytocin
that are experienced

2833
02:00:54,430 --> 02:01:00,430
are at least on par with and in
fact, more often, more dramatic

2834
02:01:00,430 --> 02:01:02,920
in response to allogrooming
than in response

2835
02:01:02,920 --> 02:01:04,700
to other forms of touch.

2836
02:01:04,700 --> 02:01:07,690
So the point here
is that allogrooming

2837
02:01:07,690 --> 02:01:10,240
is a prosocial
behavior that tends

2838
02:01:10,240 --> 02:01:13,300
to associate with
and promote feelings

2839
02:01:13,300 --> 02:01:15,280
of well-being and happiness.

2840
02:01:15,280 --> 02:01:17,150
And this is not
a trivial effect.

2841
02:01:17,150 --> 02:01:20,170
If you look at the brain imaging
data or other forms of data

2842
02:01:20,170 --> 02:01:23,170
on this, allogrooming
is a very powerful form

2843
02:01:23,170 --> 02:01:26,590
of bonding between individuals
that's completely nonverbal.

2844
02:01:26,590 --> 02:01:28,833
In fact, most often it
doesn't involve eye contact.

2845
02:01:28,833 --> 02:01:31,000
I suppose two people could
be looking at one another

2846
02:01:31,000 --> 02:01:32,800
grooming one another,
but typically, this

2847
02:01:32,800 --> 02:01:36,010
is done from the
side or from behind.

2848
02:01:36,010 --> 02:01:38,830
Why did I bring up
the paper on pets?

2849
02:01:38,830 --> 02:01:43,150
Well it turns out that
when humans stroke dogs,

2850
02:01:43,150 --> 02:01:45,610
or brush their
dogs or stroke cats

2851
02:01:45,610 --> 02:01:48,490
or brush their cats,
et cetera, that

2852
02:01:48,490 --> 02:01:50,800
is a form of human to
animal allogrooming.

2853
02:01:50,800 --> 02:01:55,670
And it's one in which
both the pet and the human

2854
02:01:55,670 --> 02:01:58,790
receive huge
increases in oxytocin

2855
02:01:58,790 --> 02:02:01,910
and other related neurochemicals
that make us feel bonded.

2856
02:02:01,910 --> 02:02:04,490
I bring this up because
the Harvard longitudinal

2857
02:02:04,490 --> 02:02:06,920
study on happiness,
and many, many others,

2858
02:02:06,920 --> 02:02:09,110
if not hundreds of other
studies on happiness,

2859
02:02:09,110 --> 02:02:12,163
point to the importance of
quality social connection.

2860
02:02:12,163 --> 02:02:13,580
You hear this over
and over again.

2861
02:02:13,580 --> 02:02:15,110
People on their
deathbeds don't say

2862
02:02:15,110 --> 02:02:16,490
they wish they had worked more.

2863
02:02:16,490 --> 02:02:19,070
People on their deathbeds
talk about the richness

2864
02:02:19,070 --> 02:02:20,750
of social connections
or the wish

2865
02:02:20,750 --> 02:02:23,270
that they had invested
more in social connections.

2866
02:02:23,270 --> 02:02:25,610
I think a lot of people
think of social connections

2867
02:02:25,610 --> 02:02:30,680
only in terms of travel with
or conversation with others.

2868
02:02:30,680 --> 02:02:35,090
But much of what we perceive
as deep social connections

2869
02:02:35,090 --> 02:02:38,060
also involves physical contact.

2870
02:02:38,060 --> 02:02:40,520
And that's something
that's deeply rooted

2871
02:02:40,520 --> 02:02:41,990
in our evolutionary biology.

2872
02:02:41,990 --> 02:02:44,690
And it's present both in us
and in non-human primates.

2873
02:02:44,690 --> 02:02:48,200
And it's clear
that we can engage

2874
02:02:48,200 --> 02:02:52,490
in these kinds of pro-social,
non verbal, non eye contact

2875
02:02:52,490 --> 02:02:56,150
type behaviors through things
like non-sexual tactile

2876
02:02:56,150 --> 02:02:57,500
touch, a.k.a.

2877
02:02:57,500 --> 02:02:58,220
allogrooming.

2878
02:02:58,220 --> 02:03:00,720
So we've been talking about a
number of the different things

2879
02:03:00,720 --> 02:03:03,530
that one can do in order to
increase levels of happiness.

2880
02:03:03,530 --> 02:03:05,480
And certainly,
before we conclude

2881
02:03:05,480 --> 02:03:08,270
today, I'm going to
touch back into not just

2882
02:03:08,270 --> 02:03:10,740
synthetic happiness and the
various things we can do,

2883
02:03:10,740 --> 02:03:13,640
such as prosocial
spending, allogrooming,

2884
02:03:13,640 --> 02:03:16,250
social connection, et cetera.

2885
02:03:16,250 --> 02:03:19,040
But also things
related to happiness

2886
02:03:19,040 --> 02:03:24,650
that involve focus on vocation
and work and pursuit of goals.

2887
02:03:24,650 --> 02:03:26,450
Because as I mentioned
at the beginning,

2888
02:03:26,450 --> 02:03:29,348
those are also
critical to increasing

2889
02:03:29,348 --> 02:03:30,890
our state of happiness,
and certainly

2890
02:03:30,890 --> 02:03:32,690
our state of security
and the feeling

2891
02:03:32,690 --> 02:03:34,790
that we can provide for
ourselves and perhaps

2892
02:03:34,790 --> 02:03:35,940
for others, as well.

2893
02:03:35,940 --> 02:03:38,010
So we will talk about that.

2894
02:03:38,010 --> 02:03:40,370
But I think it's also
important to talk

2895
02:03:40,370 --> 02:03:43,460
about this notion of
choice and choices,

2896
02:03:43,460 --> 02:03:46,730
and whether or not having
a lot of freedom to choose

2897
02:03:46,730 --> 02:03:50,900
or limited freedom in choosing
what we do and what we get,

2898
02:03:50,900 --> 02:03:53,160
and what we are able
to pursue in life,

2899
02:03:53,160 --> 02:03:56,420
how that relates to
both natural happiness

2900
02:03:56,420 --> 02:03:58,130
and synthetic happiness.

2901
02:03:58,130 --> 02:04:00,710
Dan Gilbert and
others have explored

2902
02:04:00,710 --> 02:04:03,140
this issue of freedom
of choice and how

2903
02:04:03,140 --> 02:04:04,980
it relates to happiness.

2904
02:04:04,980 --> 02:04:07,520
And there I must
say, the findings

2905
02:04:07,520 --> 02:04:10,700
are incredibly counterintuitive.

2906
02:04:10,700 --> 02:04:15,210
But very, very well supported
by all of their data.

2907
02:04:15,210 --> 02:04:18,720
I'm going to summarize a large
amount of those studies at once

2908
02:04:18,720 --> 02:04:20,640
by saying the following.

2909
02:04:20,640 --> 02:04:22,557
Dan's laboratory and
other laboratories

2910
02:04:22,557 --> 02:04:24,390
have done experiments
where they give people

2911
02:04:24,390 --> 02:04:26,080
a series of options.

2912
02:04:26,080 --> 02:04:28,200
And one of the more
classic examples, they

2913
02:04:28,200 --> 02:04:30,540
give people the opportunity
to rate a number

2914
02:04:30,540 --> 02:04:32,490
of different
paintings or pictures

2915
02:04:32,490 --> 02:04:36,427
in ascending or descending
order of preference.

2916
02:04:36,427 --> 02:04:38,010
In other words,
they're deciding which

2917
02:04:38,010 --> 02:04:40,680
ones they like most which
ones they like least.

2918
02:04:40,680 --> 02:04:43,440
Then what's interesting
is the experimenter

2919
02:04:43,440 --> 02:04:45,360
will vary the
extent to which they

2920
02:04:45,360 --> 02:04:47,080
have to stick to that choice.

2921
02:04:47,080 --> 02:04:48,810
So this could be
sticking to the choice

2922
02:04:48,810 --> 02:04:51,150
by receiving that
painting to take home.

2923
02:04:51,150 --> 02:04:53,790
Or in another
experiment, it was having

2924
02:04:53,790 --> 02:04:55,380
to make a choice
between giving up

2925
02:04:55,380 --> 02:04:58,800
one photograph that they,
the research subject took,

2926
02:04:58,800 --> 02:05:00,480
or another photograph
that they took.

2927
02:05:00,480 --> 02:05:02,310
One of the photographs
was going to go off

2928
02:05:02,310 --> 02:05:05,250
to a publication, another one
they could keep for themselves.

2929
02:05:05,250 --> 02:05:07,590
And the conditions
in that experiment

2930
02:05:07,590 --> 02:05:10,930
were either that you
had to make the decision

2931
02:05:10,930 --> 02:05:13,980
and it was final, that is,
you could keep one and rate

2932
02:05:13,980 --> 02:05:16,470
your decision, or
you could keep one

2933
02:05:16,470 --> 02:05:18,870
and then you had the
opportunity to swap out

2934
02:05:18,870 --> 02:05:21,340
that picture for the other
one at some later time.

2935
02:05:21,340 --> 02:05:23,460
In other words, these
experiments really

2936
02:05:23,460 --> 02:05:25,920
weren't about rating pictures,
they were really about

2937
02:05:25,920 --> 02:05:29,760
whether or not constraining
your choice, meaning

2938
02:05:29,760 --> 02:05:31,500
forcing somebody
to make a choice

2939
02:05:31,500 --> 02:05:34,830
and stick to that choice, led
to greater levels or lesser

2940
02:05:34,830 --> 02:05:38,040
levels of happiness and
satisfaction with that choice.

2941
02:05:38,040 --> 02:05:41,010
And what they find
consistently is

2942
02:05:41,010 --> 02:05:45,840
that when people have an
ongoing set of choices

2943
02:05:45,840 --> 02:05:48,418
it leads to reduced
levels of happiness.

2944
02:05:48,418 --> 02:05:50,460
Now that might come as
surprising to many of you,

2945
02:05:50,460 --> 02:05:52,410
but I want to be clear
about what this means.

2946
02:05:52,410 --> 02:05:56,460
This is not to say that having a
lot of choices of what you like

2947
02:05:56,460 --> 02:05:59,790
most leads to lesser happiness.

2948
02:05:59,790 --> 02:06:02,850
And that having fewer
choices about things

2949
02:06:02,850 --> 02:06:06,270
you do, or objects you
acquire, et cetera,

2950
02:06:06,270 --> 02:06:08,910
leads to greater happiness.

2951
02:06:08,910 --> 02:06:11,820
What this set of
experiments really points to

2952
02:06:11,820 --> 02:06:15,510
is that when we make a
choice, if we are forced

2953
02:06:15,510 --> 02:06:18,060
to stick to that
choice we tend to be

2954
02:06:18,060 --> 02:06:21,060
far happier with that
choice than if we maintain

2955
02:06:21,060 --> 02:06:23,710
the option to change our mind.

2956
02:06:23,710 --> 02:06:26,430
The results of these experiments
are extremely informative,

2957
02:06:26,430 --> 02:06:30,130
I believe, in terms of
understanding our real life

2958
02:06:30,130 --> 02:06:30,630
happiness.

2959
02:06:30,630 --> 02:06:33,240
That is, happiness
outside the laboratory.

2960
02:06:33,240 --> 02:06:35,550
But I think they are
often misunderstood

2961
02:06:35,550 --> 02:06:37,590
as meaning that if we
have a lot of choices

2962
02:06:37,590 --> 02:06:40,260
we tend to be less happy than
if we have fewer choices.

2963
02:06:40,260 --> 02:06:41,340
That is not the case.

2964
02:06:41,340 --> 02:06:44,310
Having freedom of
choice is terrific.

2965
02:06:44,310 --> 02:06:47,940
And actually, correlates with
elevated levels of happiness.

2966
02:06:47,940 --> 02:06:50,910
But once we make
our choice, it's

2967
02:06:50,910 --> 02:06:53,910
clearly the case that
killing all other choices

2968
02:06:53,910 --> 02:06:55,740
or having all other
options killed

2969
02:06:55,740 --> 02:06:59,010
for us increases our
satisfaction with the choice

2970
02:06:59,010 --> 02:06:59,970
that we've made.

2971
02:06:59,970 --> 02:07:03,960
Whereas, leaving doors open,
leaving options open greatly

2972
02:07:03,960 --> 02:07:07,110
diminishes our sense
of satisfaction.

2973
02:07:07,110 --> 02:07:10,570
This has been exported to any
number of different domains.

2974
02:07:10,570 --> 02:07:14,430
So this has been exported to
the domain of making choices

2975
02:07:14,430 --> 02:07:19,800
about what college to go to or
what partner to select in life.

2976
02:07:19,800 --> 02:07:21,990
In every one of
those instances, we

2977
02:07:21,990 --> 02:07:23,760
see that our happiness
with our choice

2978
02:07:23,760 --> 02:07:25,680
is very much related
to that choice

2979
02:07:25,680 --> 02:07:30,558
being either the only one or
one of very few other options.

2980
02:07:30,558 --> 02:07:32,850
There are a number of different
ways to interpret this.

2981
02:07:32,850 --> 02:07:34,920
Through the lens
of neuroscience we

2982
02:07:34,920 --> 02:07:38,400
might say that the
prefrontal cortex,

2983
02:07:38,400 --> 02:07:41,850
the area of the brain that's
involved in decision making

2984
02:07:41,850 --> 02:07:44,700
and evaluating
different options,

2985
02:07:44,700 --> 02:07:48,420
is an area of the brain
that's vital, frankly,

2986
02:07:48,420 --> 02:07:51,240
to our evolution as human
beings and to our daily life

2987
02:07:51,240 --> 02:07:52,915
and to our whole life.

2988
02:07:52,915 --> 02:07:54,540
It is, of course,
the thing that allows

2989
02:07:54,540 --> 02:07:57,780
us to evaluate different rule
sets, to change rule sets,

2990
02:07:57,780 --> 02:08:00,780
to switch contexts and to
create meaning, et cetera.

2991
02:08:00,780 --> 02:08:02,730
To interpret what's
good what's bad.

2992
02:08:02,730 --> 02:08:04,990
But it's also a
fairly costly process,

2993
02:08:04,990 --> 02:08:06,900
meaning it's very
metabolically demanding.

2994
02:08:06,900 --> 02:08:09,300
And there's an entire
literature related

2995
02:08:09,300 --> 02:08:10,830
to what's called ego depletion.

2996
02:08:10,830 --> 02:08:12,990
This is certainly a topic
for a future podcast.

2997
02:08:12,990 --> 02:08:15,510
But ego depletion essentially
says that if I have you

2998
02:08:15,510 --> 02:08:21,220
attend very intensely to a
given task, for instance,

2999
02:08:21,220 --> 02:08:23,580
asking you to count
backwards from 1,000 to 0

3000
02:08:23,580 --> 02:08:25,470
in increments of 13.

3001
02:08:25,470 --> 02:08:28,230
And then have you
switch about halfway

3002
02:08:28,230 --> 02:08:30,510
through, that's hard
for a lot of people.

3003
02:08:30,510 --> 02:08:32,580
If I have you do that,
then your ability

3004
02:08:32,580 --> 02:08:37,680
to suppress impulsive behavior
and to do a hard cognitive

3005
02:08:37,680 --> 02:08:40,410
or physical task immediately
after that is actually

3006
02:08:40,410 --> 02:08:40,920
suppressed.

3007
02:08:40,920 --> 02:08:42,090
This so-called ego depletion.

3008
02:08:42,090 --> 02:08:43,882
It relates to a number
of different things,

3009
02:08:43,882 --> 02:08:46,770
but it certainly
relates to engagement

3010
02:08:46,770 --> 02:08:48,240
of the prefrontal
cortex, which is

3011
02:08:48,240 --> 02:08:49,830
very metabolically demanding.

3012
02:08:49,830 --> 02:08:53,910
So evaluating choices and
doing computation of numbers

3013
02:08:53,910 --> 02:08:56,160
or attending to
things with your mind

3014
02:08:56,160 --> 02:08:58,200
and forcing yourself
to focus intensely

3015
02:08:58,200 --> 02:09:00,360
is metabolically demanding.

3016
02:09:00,360 --> 02:09:02,280
And that's a limited
resource that

3017
02:09:02,280 --> 02:09:05,010
can be reset by things like
sleep and non sleep deep rest

3018
02:09:05,010 --> 02:09:06,900
or idle time or letting
your mind wander.

3019
02:09:06,900 --> 02:09:08,730
In that case a
positive mind wandering

3020
02:09:08,730 --> 02:09:11,920
to allow your brain to
reset its ability to focus.

3021
02:09:11,920 --> 02:09:15,250
But the other thing
that it does is

3022
02:09:15,250 --> 02:09:18,520
it impacts the reward
circuitry of the brain,

3023
02:09:18,520 --> 02:09:20,980
the so-called dopamine reward
circuitry and other reward

3024
02:09:20,980 --> 02:09:23,262
circuitry of the brain.

3025
02:09:23,262 --> 02:09:24,970
And here I'm painting
with a broad brush.

3026
02:09:24,970 --> 02:09:29,060
But it essentially divides
them such that for instance,

3027
02:09:29,060 --> 02:09:32,260
if a given choice of
a let's say a partner

3028
02:09:32,260 --> 02:09:34,900
or maybe buying ourselves
an article of clothing,

3029
02:09:34,900 --> 02:09:37,535
not that I want to compare
selection of a life partner

3030
02:09:37,535 --> 02:09:39,160
to selection of an
article of clothing.

3031
02:09:39,160 --> 02:09:40,810
But just to give
multiple examples.

3032
02:09:40,810 --> 02:09:44,980
Might give us, and here
it's arbitrary units, x

3033
02:09:44,980 --> 02:09:47,950
units of dopamine increase.

3034
02:09:47,950 --> 02:09:50,470
Well, if we buy that
article of clothing or we

3035
02:09:50,470 --> 02:09:52,300
select that life
partner, and then

3036
02:09:52,300 --> 02:09:55,240
we emerge from the
store or the wedding

3037
02:09:55,240 --> 02:09:58,970
and we are focused on what
we purchased for ourselves,

3038
02:09:58,970 --> 02:10:03,610
our choice, or our life partner
choice, and only that, well

3039
02:10:03,610 --> 02:10:07,370
then there's a certain amount of
neurochemical reward associated

3040
02:10:07,370 --> 02:10:07,870
with that.

3041
02:10:07,870 --> 02:10:09,460
And happiness and well-being.

3042
02:10:09,460 --> 02:10:13,970
But it's also very
clear that if we

3043
02:10:13,970 --> 02:10:18,300
leave those choices, the store
or our wedding for instance,

3044
02:10:18,300 --> 02:10:20,960
or a life with somebody for
a moment, even just mentally,

3045
02:10:20,960 --> 02:10:23,150
and start thinking
about the other options

3046
02:10:23,150 --> 02:10:25,670
that we might
entertain as possible.

3047
02:10:25,670 --> 02:10:28,790
If those are still open to
us in reality or in our mind,

3048
02:10:28,790 --> 02:10:32,630
well then our reward circuitry
becomes fractured in a way.

3049
02:10:32,630 --> 02:10:35,420
Not physically fractured,
but less attention

3050
02:10:35,420 --> 02:10:38,420
is devoted to the reward
circuitry associated

3051
02:10:38,420 --> 02:10:40,100
with our choice.

3052
02:10:40,100 --> 02:10:43,820
And as a consequence, instead
of it being x units of dopamine,

3053
02:10:43,820 --> 02:10:48,320
it's x divided by however
many other choices

3054
02:10:48,320 --> 02:10:51,500
we might have available to
us in our mind or in reality.

3055
02:10:51,500 --> 02:10:53,840
So instead of, and again,
these are arbitrary units,

3056
02:10:53,840 --> 02:10:55,905
but instead of a certain
amount of reward,

3057
02:10:55,905 --> 02:10:57,530
it's a certain amount
of reward divided

3058
02:10:57,530 --> 02:10:59,480
by the number of
other options that we

3059
02:10:59,480 --> 02:11:03,990
might be considering as
alternatives to what we chose.

3060
02:11:03,990 --> 02:11:06,950
And I think this is a
very important aspect

3061
02:11:06,950 --> 02:11:11,510
of understanding how limiting
our choices after we've

3062
02:11:11,510 --> 02:11:14,690
made them is a
vital part of what

3063
02:11:14,690 --> 02:11:16,320
we call synthetic happiness.

3064
02:11:16,320 --> 02:11:18,080
In fact, we could
even go so far as

3065
02:11:18,080 --> 02:11:20,720
to say that focusing on
the choices we've made

3066
02:11:20,720 --> 02:11:24,470
and really investing in
those choices as good ones,

3067
02:11:24,470 --> 02:11:26,847
or great ones, and
really trying to limit

3068
02:11:26,847 --> 02:11:28,430
our thinking to the
choices that we've

3069
02:11:28,430 --> 02:11:31,490
made once we've
made them is perhaps

3070
02:11:31,490 --> 02:11:34,340
also important to our
natural happiness.

3071
02:11:34,340 --> 02:11:38,810
Because it's so inextricably
entwined with what

3072
02:11:38,810 --> 02:11:41,070
we think of as a good life.

3073
02:11:41,070 --> 02:11:44,150
And what I mean by that
is if we are constantly

3074
02:11:44,150 --> 02:11:46,350
in a mode of evaluative
decision making,

3075
02:11:46,350 --> 02:11:48,080
even after we've
made a decision,

3076
02:11:48,080 --> 02:11:52,070
we are not neurochemically
nor psychologically able

3077
02:11:52,070 --> 02:11:54,762
to extract the feelings
of happiness associated

3078
02:11:54,762 --> 02:11:55,970
with the choice that we made.

3079
02:11:55,970 --> 02:11:57,680
So we've talked about a
number of different dimensions

3080
02:11:57,680 --> 02:12:00,230
of happiness, both in synthetic
and natural happiness.

3081
02:12:00,230 --> 02:12:02,900
And some of the more
counterintuitive aspects

3082
02:12:02,900 --> 02:12:04,490
of happiness.

3083
02:12:04,490 --> 02:12:06,470
For instance, that
people tend to adjust

3084
02:12:06,470 --> 02:12:11,620
their levels of happiness not
regardless but often in spite

3085
02:12:11,620 --> 02:12:13,700
of their life circumstances.

3086
02:12:13,700 --> 02:12:17,140
But as we emphasized earlier
in the episode, that is not

3087
02:12:17,140 --> 02:12:20,020
to say, at least the
research does not directly

3088
02:12:20,020 --> 02:12:23,710
support the idea that
a major trauma or loss

3089
02:12:23,710 --> 02:12:25,340
won't impact our happiness.

3090
02:12:25,340 --> 02:12:26,950
In fact, it tends to.

3091
02:12:26,950 --> 02:12:29,320
And that's why it's
important that people access

3092
02:12:29,320 --> 02:12:31,990
resources and work devoted
to overcoming trauma, which

3093
02:12:31,990 --> 02:12:34,430
certainly exists out there.

3094
02:12:34,430 --> 02:12:37,540
And of course, there are
the longitudinal studies

3095
02:12:37,540 --> 02:12:41,650
in short term studies showing
that income level and material

3096
02:12:41,650 --> 02:12:46,030
things don't necessarily scale
with happiness, and vise versa.

3097
02:12:46,030 --> 02:12:49,240
And yet, we also acknowledged
early in the episode

3098
02:12:49,240 --> 02:12:51,760
that while indeed money
can't buy happiness,

3099
02:12:51,760 --> 02:12:53,110
it can buffer stress.

3100
02:12:53,110 --> 02:12:56,470
And while work doesn't
necessarily bring happiness,

3101
02:12:56,470 --> 02:13:00,190
per se, work can bring
a tremendous feeling

3102
02:13:00,190 --> 02:13:03,400
of meaning and resources
which can then put you

3103
02:13:03,400 --> 02:13:07,030
into context in which things
like prosocial contact

3104
02:13:07,030 --> 02:13:12,160
and enhanced bonds and
caretaking of others and of you

3105
02:13:12,160 --> 02:13:13,210
can be enhanced.

3106
02:13:13,210 --> 02:13:16,390
So it would be unfair
and in fact, inaccurate,

3107
02:13:16,390 --> 02:13:19,450
to simply view happiness
through the lens of money

3108
02:13:19,450 --> 02:13:21,980
doesn't matter, it's all
about social connection.

3109
02:13:21,980 --> 02:13:23,890
And so on and so forth.

3110
02:13:23,890 --> 02:13:26,600
Absolutely, social
connection is important,

3111
02:13:26,600 --> 02:13:29,093
which is why we spent some
minutes talking about some

3112
02:13:29,093 --> 02:13:30,760
of the ways to enhance
social connection

3113
02:13:30,760 --> 02:13:33,010
both with other human
beings and other animals,

3114
02:13:33,010 --> 02:13:35,680
and them with us.

3115
02:13:35,680 --> 02:13:39,280
I think there's a opportunity
here to take the research

3116
02:13:39,280 --> 02:13:43,150
on happiness, the research
on the neuroscience of what

3117
02:13:43,150 --> 02:13:47,440
happiness and gratitude and
prosocial connection tells us,

3118
02:13:47,440 --> 02:13:50,870
and to combine it into a
bit of a model or a toolkit,

3119
02:13:50,870 --> 02:13:51,470
if you will.

3120
02:13:51,470 --> 02:13:53,860
And I think indeed, this
will be a toolkit in one

3121
02:13:53,860 --> 02:13:56,650
of our future toolkit episodes,
likely merged with the toolkit

3122
02:13:56,650 --> 02:13:59,450
on gratitude, which
we haven't done yet.

3123
02:13:59,450 --> 02:14:04,390
And perhaps even we will do an
entire episode on social bonds

3124
02:14:04,390 --> 02:14:06,790
and how to enhance or
build social bonds.

3125
02:14:06,790 --> 02:14:10,413
Or at least what the
science tells us about that.

3126
02:14:10,413 --> 02:14:11,830
If we take a step
back and we look

3127
02:14:11,830 --> 02:14:15,250
at the concept of happiness,
we can make a couple

3128
02:14:15,250 --> 02:14:17,050
of absolute statements.

3129
02:14:17,050 --> 02:14:19,490
That is, statements that I
think very few people, if any,

3130
02:14:19,490 --> 02:14:20,110
would contest.

3131
02:14:20,110 --> 02:14:22,690
First of all, there's no
single molecule or chemical

3132
02:14:22,690 --> 02:14:25,330
associated with happiness,
but that the chemical milieu

3133
02:14:25,330 --> 02:14:29,650
of the brain and body
is important for setting

3134
02:14:29,650 --> 02:14:33,470
the stage or the
opportunity for happiness.

3135
02:14:33,470 --> 02:14:37,160
Hence, why there are treatments
aimed at alleviating depression

3136
02:14:37,160 --> 02:14:40,280
or mania that target certain
neurochemical systems

3137
02:14:40,280 --> 02:14:41,990
and hormone systems.

3138
02:14:41,990 --> 02:14:45,380
Happiness, at least the
way I'm framing it today,

3139
02:14:45,380 --> 02:14:46,830
has essentially two components.

3140
02:14:46,830 --> 02:14:49,190
One is meaning.

3141
02:14:49,190 --> 02:14:54,470
That is, what sort of meaning
do certain types of interactions

3142
02:14:54,470 --> 02:14:58,310
or behaviors, could be work,
could be social interactions,

3143
02:14:58,310 --> 02:15:01,280
et cetera, carry for us?

3144
02:15:01,280 --> 02:15:04,035
And nested in that is this
concept of connection.

3145
02:15:04,035 --> 02:15:06,410
And we talked a bit about
tools for enhancing connection.

3146
02:15:06,410 --> 02:15:08,930
Things like eye contact, but
